1f336-fe0f.description: A bright red Mexican chili pepper, slightly curled and with a green stem. May be used to represent something “hot and spicy,” figuratively or literally, as a dish on a restaurant menu. Hot Pepper was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f344.title: Mushroom
1f344.description: The edible fungus of the mushroom, depicted as a toadstool with a white-spotted red cap and stem. Mushroom was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f330.title: Chestnut
1f330.description: The reddish-brown, acorn-shaped chestnut, tapering to a sharp tip from its light brown base on most platforms. A popular roasted snack associated with autumn and Christmas. May be used for other edible nuts (e.g., walnuts) or sexual slang. Chestnut was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f35e.title: Bread
1f35e.description: A loaf of white or wheat bread, as before it is sliced for toast or sandwiches. Bread was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f9c0.title: Cheese Wedge
1f9c0.description: A wedge of yellow-orange cheese with holes, like a Swiss, but used for the food in general. May be used for various cheese-related slang expressions (e.g., “cheesy,” “say cheese,” “big cheese”). Cheese Wedge was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f356.title: Meat on Bone
1f356.description: A hunk of unspecified meat on a white bone, as associated with cartoon cavepersons or food in anime and manga (Japanese ano niku, “that meat”). This emoji was shown as a steak in Android 4.4. Meat on Bone was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f357.title: Poultry Leg
1f357.description: A crispy brown leg (drumstick) of chicken, duck, turkey, or other poultry on the bone, as roasted at Thanksgiving or Christmas dinner or fried at fast-food restaurants. Poultry Leg was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f354.title: Hamburger
1f354.description: A burger with a beef patty, usually depicted on a sesame bun with cheese, lettuce, and tomato—making it a cheeseburger, though officially called Hamburger by Unicode. Platforms stack the ingredients in various orders. Google previously placed the cheese under the patty, a "controversy" CEO Sundar Pichai addressed in 2018. Hamburger was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f35f.title: French Fries
1f35f.description: Thin-cut, golden-brown French fries, served in a red carton, as at McDonald’s. Apple features Smiling Face With Smiling Eyes on its carton. French Fries was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f355.title: Pizza
1f355.description: A slice of pepperoni pizza, topped with black olives on Google. WhatsApp adds green pepper, Samsung white onion. Pizza was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Slice of Pizza” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f32d.title: Hot Dog
1f32d.description: The cooked sausage of a hot dog in a sliced bun and drizzled with yellow mustard, as eaten at a baseball game. Hot Dog was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f32e.title: Taco
1f32e.description: A Mexican or Tex-Mex taco on a hard or soft corn tortilla, filled with such ingredients as beef, lettuce, tomato, cheese, and onion. Apple’s design resembles a carne asada taco, with cilantro and white onion. Taco was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f32f.title: Burrito
1f32f.description: A Mexican or Tex-Mex burrito, featuring a wrapped flour tortilla filled with such ingredients as beef, rice, beans, cheese, tomato, lettuce, and sour cream. Served in foil on several major platforms, suggesting a Mission burrito associated with San Francisco. Not to be confused with the Stuffed Flatbread. Burrito was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f373.title: Cooking
1f373.description: An egg with yolk frying in a skillet, as prepared sunny-side up. Though associated with breakfast, the emoji represents the general action of cooking and related concepts. Cooking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f372.title: Pot of Food
1f372.description: A pot, as a casserole dish, filled with a warm and hearty beef or vegetable stew on most platforms. Samsung’s design resembles a bowl of ramen or other noodle dish, with chopsticks. Generally used for eating and cooking (“a meal”), and commonly associated with soup or Japanese nabe. Pot of Food was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f37f.title: Popcorn
1f37f.description: The buttery-white snack of popcorn brimming in a classic red-and-white-striped carton, as enjoyed at a movie theater. May be used to express engagement (“edge of one’s seat”). Popcorn was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f371.title: Bento Box
1f371.description: A Japanese bento, a lunch box divided into portions of rice, vegetables, and meat or seafood, such as sushi or fried shrimp. Bento Box was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f358.title: Rice Cracker
1f358.description: A Japanese senbei, or rice cracker, wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed, a snack commonly enjoyed with green tea. Rice Cracker was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f359.title: Rice Ball
1f359.description: A Japanese onigiri, a cone-shaped ball of white rice, a snack wrapped with a sheet of nori, or seaweed. Rice Ball was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f35a.title: Cooked Rice
1f35a.description: A bowl of steamed white rice, a staple component of cuisine throughout Asia. Bowl color varies across platforms, though is often white. Cooked Rice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f35b.title: Curry Rice
1f35b.description: A plate of orange-brown curry with vegetables or meat, served with a mound of white rice. May represent kare-raisu, or Japanese curry, though commonly associated with India and other Asian cuisines. Curry Rice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Curry and Rice” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f35c.title: Steaming Bowl
1f35c.description: A bowl of steaming-hot food. Depicted as Japanese ramen (noodles in broth) with chopsticks on most platforms, though it can represent a warm meal more generally. Samsung’s design resembles Pot of Food. Steaming Bowl was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f35d.title: Spaghetti
1f35d.description: A plate of Italian spaghetti with tomato sauce, as a bolognese, with a fork twirling its long, thin noodles. Garnished with a green herb, as parsley, on some platforms. Spaghetti was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f360.title: Roasted Sweet Potato
1f360.description: A sweet potato depicted with textured purple, orange, or brown skin and sliced in half to show its golden-brown flesh. Sometimes called a yam, though they are unrelated. Not to be confused with the Potato. Commonly roasted as a snack in East Asia during winter, much as squash and pumpkin are popular in the United States during fall/autumn. Used as an offering to the full moon in Japan during the Moon Viewing harvest festival. Roasted Sweet Potato was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f362.title: Oden
1f362.description: A skewer of three bites of Japanese oden, a winter dish made with fishcakes, tofu, konnyaku, and a variety of other ingredients, including boiled eggs. Often served as a stew or skewered and dipped into soy sauce. Resembles the Dango and may be used for other skewered foods (e.g., shish kebab, roasting marshmallows) or spears. Oden was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f363.title: Sushi
1f363.description: Japanese sushi, generally depicted as two pieces of raw pinkish-orange fish, as tuna or salmon, on white rice (nigiri). Some platforms show the cylindrical maki, a piece of seafood, vegetables, and white rice wrapped in seaweed (nori). Sushi was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f364.title: Fried Shrimp
1f364.description: A prawn or shrimp breaded and deep-fried golden-brown. Known as ebi furai in Japan but commonly called shrimp tempura and served in a bento box. Not to be confused with the Shrimp. Fried Shrimp was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f365.title: Fish Cake With Swirl
1f365.description: A slice of Japanese narutomaki, a ridged fishcake of processed whitefish with an iconic pink swirl, often served in ramen or oden. Thanks to its distinct swirl, may be used for flair. Fish Cake With Swirl was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Fish Cake With Swirl Design” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f361.title: Dango
1f361.description: A Japanese sweet dumpling made from rice flour and served on a skewer. Depicted as a botchan dango, comprising a pink, white or light yellow, and green ball, as colored by red beans, egg, and green tea. Resembles the Oden and featured in the Moon Viewing Ceremony, used in the Japanese festival to celebrate the full moon. Dango was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f980.title: Crab
1f980.description: A crab, a squat crustacean with pincers. Depicted as a reddish-orange crab (as cooked) shown from above, with a round, shelled body, shorted, tentacle-like eyes, and ten legs, the top two of which are large pincers. May be used to represent crab as food or metaphorical senses of crab (e.g., crabby). Often used to represent ♋ Cancer, the Crab, in the Western zodiac. Not to be confused with 🦞 Lobster. Facebook’s pincers have black tips. Crab was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f366.title: Soft Ice Cream
1f366.description: A swirl of soft-serve ice cream atop a wafer-style cone, white or cream-colored, as vanilla, on most platforms. Facebook’s design suggests strawberry. May be used more generally for ice cream, frozen yogurt, and frozen treats. Soft Ice Cream was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f367.title: Shaved Ice
1f367.description: A mound of shaved ice (snow cone) served in a dessert bowl with a short spoon, flavored with a cherry-red syrup on many platforms. Associated with Hawaiian shave ice or Japanese kakigori. Shaved Ice was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f368.title: Ice Cream
1f368.description: One or more scoops of ice cream in a dessert bowl, variously topped with sprinkles, wafer rolls, or cherry and syrup. Flavors vary from vanilla, chocolate, and/or strawberry across platforms. Ice Cream was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f369.title: Doughnut
1f369.description: A chocolate-glazed donut (or doughnut) with rainbow sprinkles. WhatsApp features a pink glaze associated with The Simpsons. May resemble the Bagel at small sizes. Doughnut was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f36a.title: Cookie
1f36a.description: A golden-brown chocolate chip cookie, or biscuit, though representing the baked treat more generally. Samsung, which features a pair of cookies, previously displayed this as two saltine crackers. Cookie was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f382.title: Birthday Cake
1f382.description: A frosted cake with lit candles, as presented for a birthday celebration. The style of cake widely varies across platforms. With white frosting and strawberries, Apple and Google’s designs suggest a Japanese Christmas cake. Other vendors depict a chocolate, pink, and/or sponge cake. Birthday Cake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f370.title: Shortcake
1f370.description: A slice of strawberry shortcake, layered with whipped cream and topped with a whole strawberry. Like the Birthday Cake, may be used to represent birthday celebrations or cake in general. Shortcake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f36b.title: Chocolate Bar
1f36b.description: A block of dark chocolate, usually shown in a red foil wrapper peeled back to show squares of the candy. WhatsApp displays the wrapper in purple, a color commonly associated with Cadbury chocolate. Chocolate Bar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f36c.title: Candy
1f36c.description: A small piece of round, hard sugar candy, as handed out on Halloween, wrapped with two twists on its ends. Candy and wrapper color vary widely by platform. Facebook’s design resembles a classic, unwrapped red-and-white peppermint. May also be called sweets or lollies. Candy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f36d.title: Lollipop
1f36d.description: A colorful swirl of hard candy on a stick, called a lollipop. Color varies widely by platform: Google displays rainbow colors, Android shades of pink, and Samsung a candy-cane-colored pinwheel. "Lollipop" was the name of version 5 of Google's Android operating system. Lollipop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f36e.title: Custard
1f36e.description: A golden-yellow custard dessert, as a crème caramel or flan, topped with a layer of caramel. Shown on a plate, molded in a ramekin-shape and often in a pool of caramel sauce. Custard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f36f.title: Honey Pot
1f36f.description: A golden-yellow pot of honey, as made by bees and desired by bears. Shown with the sweet substance oozing down its sides, often with a honey dipper inside the small vessel. May be used figuratively, as the term of endearment “honey.” Honey Pot was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f37c.title: Baby Bottle
1f37c.description: A bottle of milk or formula, as or fed to a baby, with a bluish cap and rubber nipple or teat. Positioned upright or at a 45° angle, and filled to various levels, sometimes showing fill lines. Often used for newborns and childrearing. See also Breast-Feeding. Baby Bottle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f375.title: Teacup Without Handle
1f375.description: A cup of green tea, as the minty-colored Japanese matcha, usually shown on a wooden mat. Matcha is traditionally served in a small bowl that resembles a cup without a handle. Often taken as a bowl of soup, such as a split pea. Teacup Without Handle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f376.title: Sake
1f376.description: Japanese sake, an alcoholic beverage made from rice. Shown as a sake set with a carafe (tokkuri) and drinking cup (choko). Color varies widely by platform, with Apple, WhatsApp, and Twitter featuring blue, a traditional ceramic color. Samsung displays the Japanese script for “sake” in red. Sake was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Sake Bottle and Cup” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f37e.title: Bottle With Popping Cork
1f37e.description: A green bottle of champagne or sparkling wine with label, its cork popping to shoot out its bubbly contents. Used for a range of celebratory occasions, such as New Year's Eve, birthdays, weddings, or other life accomplishments. Bottle With Popping Cork was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f377.title: Wine Glass
1f377.description: Red wine served in a stemmed glass. Google previously displayed an orange-colored drink that resembled cognac. Wine Glass was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f378.title: Cocktail Glass
1f378.description: A stemmed glass with a cone-shaped bowl, used for serving cocktails. Depicted as a martini garnished with an olive. Might be gin or vodka, shaken or stirred. See also Tropical Drink. Cocktail Glass was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f379.title: Tropical Drink
1f379.description: A sunset-orange-colored tropical beverage in a stemmed glass, as a rum punch or mai tai. Served with a straw and fruit garnish. Many platforms include a cocktail umbrella, hence umbrella drink. Samsung previously featured an electric-blue concoction. See also Cocktail Glass. Tropical Drink was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f37a.title: Beer Mug
1f37a.description: A beer, as a golden-colored lager, in a frosty mug. Depicted with a frothy head spilling over the brim. Clinking Beer Mugs is a variation that displays two such beer mugs. Beer Mug was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f37b.title: Clinking Beer Mugs
1f37b.description: Two frosty mugs of beer with frothy heads being clinked together, as done at a celebratory or convivial toast (“Cheers!”). Several platforms include stylized lines to mark the clinking. See also Clinking Glasses. Clinking Beer Mugs was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f37d-fe0f.title: Fork and Knife With Plate
1f37d-fe0f.description: A silver fork and knife on either side of a white plate, as set for dinner or another meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon. Fork and Knife With Plate was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f374.title: Fork and Knife
1f374.description: A silver fork to the left of a knife, silverware or cutlery used to eat a meal. Often used more generally for eating and dining. May be paired with Spoon or used with Fork and Knife With Plate. Fork and Knife was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f52a.title: Kitchen Knife
1f52a.description: A knife with a long steel blade, as a chef uses to slice meat or vegetables. Depicted with a black or brown handle and positioned at a 45° angle, often with its point at the lower right. May be used for content concerning cooking and food preparation, but often represents various senses of cutting and stabbing. Its Unicode name, Hocho, means “kitchen knife” in Japanese and refers to a variety of knives used in Japan. Not to be confused with 🗡️ Dagger or ⚔️ Crossed Swords. Kitchen Knife was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Hocho” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3fa.title: Amphora
1f3fa.description: A tall, ceramic jar with two handles and a narrow neck and foot. Represents an amphora, as used by ancient Greeks and Romans to hold water and wine. Generally depicted as brownish-red earthenware ornamented with black and a Greek meander pattern. May represent containers like vases, pottery, museums, history, and antiquity. May also be used in relation to the zodiac sign of Aquarius, the Water-Bearer. Not to be confused with ⚱️ Funeral Urn. Amphora was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f30d.title: Globe Showing Europe-Africa
1f30d.description: A globe, showing the continents of Europe and Africa in green against blue ocean. May be used to represent various content concerning the European, African, and Atlantic regions. May also be used to represent Earth and international affairs more generally. See also 🌎 Globe Showing Americas and 🌏 Globe Showing Asia-Australia. Globe Showing Europe-Africa was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Earth Globe Europe-Africa” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f30e.title: Globe Showing Americas
1f30e.description: A globe, showing the continents of North and South America in green against blue ocean. May be used to represent various content concerning the North and South American regions as well Atlantic and Pacific regions. May also be used to represent Earth and international affairs more generally. See also 🌍 Globe Showing Europe-Africa and 🌏 Globe Showing Asia-Australia. Globe Showing Americas was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Earth Globe Americas” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f30f.title: Globe Showing Asia-Australia
1f30f.description: A globe, showing the continents of Asia and Australia in green against blue ocean. May be used to represent various content concerning the Asian, Australian, and Pacific regions. May also be used to represent Earth and international affairs more generally. See also 🌎 Globe Showing Americas and 🌍 Globe Showing Europe-Africa. Globe Showing Asia-Australia was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Earth Globe Asia-Australia” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f310.title: Globe With Meridians
1f310.description: A stylized globe, with blue meridians (longitudes) and latitude. Depicted with light-blue grid of lines on a white, blue, or empty circle. May be used as a symbol of the internet or world wide web, global communications, international affairs, connectivity and networks, time zones, coordinates, or the world more generally. May appear as an icon on Apple devices to change (language) keyboards. See also 🌎 Globe Showing Americas, 🌍 Globe Showing Europe-Africa, and 🌏 Globe Showing Asia-Australia. Globe With Meridians was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5fa-fe0f.title: World Map
1f5fa-fe0f.description: A rectangular map of the world. Generally depicted as a paper map creased at its folds, Earth’s surface shown in green on blue ocean. Commonly represent maps, travel, exploration, and geography. May also represent various content concerning the world as a whole, e.g., global or international issues. Microsoft and Samsung’s design previously depicted outlines of the continents. World Map was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5fe.title: Map of Japan
1f5fe.description: Shows a map of the country of Japan, which is the only country to have its own emoji map. Other countries can be found on the various globe emojis, or the world map emoji. Map of Japan was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Silhouette of Japan” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3d4-fe0f.title: Snow-Capped Mountain
1f3d4-fe0f.description: A mountain with snow resting at higher altitudes. Similar in appearance to the Mount Fuji emoji. Snow-Capped Mountain was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Snow Capped Mountain” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26f0-fe0f.title: Mountain
26f0-fe0f.description: A mountain shown with two peaks and blue sky. Similar to the snow capped mountain emoji. Mountain was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f30b.title: Volcano
1f30b.description: A volcano, erupting with smoke and lava. Volcano was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5fb.title: Mount Fuji
1f5fb.description: Mount Fuji (called Fuji-san in Japan) is the largest mountain in Japan. Often seen with snow on the peak in colder months of the year. It is considered lucky in Japan to dream of Mt Fuji in the first dream of the new year. Mount Fuji was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3d5-fe0f.title: Camping
1f3d5-fe0f.description: A campsite featuring a tent and a tree, and perhaps a campfire. Similar to the tent emoji. Camping was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3d6-fe0f.title: Beach With Umbrella
1f3d6-fe0f.description: A beach showing sand, and an umbrella for protection from the sun. Beach With Umbrella was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3dc-fe0f.title: Desert
1f3dc-fe0f.description: Desert was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3dd-fe0f.title: Desert Island
1f3dd-fe0f.description: Desert Island was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3de-fe0f.title: National Park
1f3de-fe0f.description: A national park, generally displayed with mountains, a river or stream, and trees. National Park was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3df-fe0f.title: Stadium
1f3df-fe0f.description: A large capacity stadium, featuring a large amount of seating for sporting fans, or people attending other shows hosted by the stadium. Stadium was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3db-fe0f.title: Classical Building
1f3db-fe0f.description: Classical Building was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3d7-fe0f.title: Building Construction
1f3d7-fe0f.description: A construction site generally depicted as a tower crane shown lifting steel or other building materials. Building Construction was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3d8-fe0f.title: Houses
1f3d8-fe0f.description: Multiple houses. Houses was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “House Buildings” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3da-fe0f.title: Derelict House
1f3da-fe0f.description: A house which is unoccupied, and has become derelict. In a state of disrepair. Derelict House was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Derelict House Building” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e0.title: House
1f3e0.description: A house, otherwise known as a home when someone is living in it. Suitable for a couple or larger family, other perhaps housemates. Distinct from an apartment building due to its detached form, this house is likely in the suburbs of a city or a rural area. House was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “House Building” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e1.title: House With Garden
1f3e1.description: A suburban-looking house, with a tree, flower, or shrubs around it in the garden. House With Garden was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e2.title: Office Building
1f3e2.description: A generic, high-rise office building. Generally found in cities, and most active during business hours. The office building shown in Twemoji 2.0 is of Twitter HQ in San Fransisco. Office Building was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e3.title: Japanese Post Office
1f3e3.description: A Japanese post office, featuring the テ Japanese postal mark on the front of the building (or showing this mark instead of the building in Microsoft’s artwork). Japanese Post Office was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e4.title: Post Office
1f3e4.description: A European-style post office. A postal horn can be seen on the front, which is commonly found in the logos of European Postal Services. Post Office was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “European Post Office” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e5.title: Hospital
1f3e5.description: A place where people are taken to receive medical care. This hospital has a large red cross on the front, often used as a symbol for health care. Hospital was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e6.title: Bank
1f3e6.description: A retail bank branch, where people can perform money-related tasks. Also a common location to find an ATM. This emoji came to also mean "slacking off" or evading responsibility in Japan, due to the BK letters being associated with the slang term bakkureru. Bank was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e8.title: Hotel
1f3e8.description: A hotel building, displayed on most platforms as a building with many windows and a letter H on the front. Can be easily confused with the Love Hotel, or Hospital emoji. Microsoft this emoji as a bed, when viewed using Windows. Hotel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e9.title: Love Hotel
1f3e9.description: A love hotel is a hotel that can be hired by the hour instead of as accommodation for the evening. Sometimes mistaken for a get well soon emoji due to the similarity in appearance to the hospital. The Microsoft version of this emoji previously displaying a bed with a heart above it. Love Hotel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3ea.title: Convenience Store
1f3ea.description: A shop that is generally open for longer hours than a regular supermarket, sometimes 24 hours per day. Sells a range of goods from snacks, meals, hygiene products and household items. Convenience Store was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3eb.title: School
1f3eb.description: A school building with multiple storeys, and a clock on the front. A place that children, or teenagers attend for their education. Displays on Windows as a collection of school-related items: an apple, ruler, and pencil. School was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3ec.title: Department Store
1f3ec.description: A large department store, selling a range of products to the general public. Shown as a large building with a billboard on most platforms, or as a shopping bag on Windows. Department Store was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3ed.title: Factory
1f3ed.description: An industrial factory, with flue-gas stacks releasing exhaust into the air. Factory was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3ef.title: Japanese Castle
1f3ef.description: A traditional Japanese Castle, usually made from stone and wood. Japanese Castle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3f0.title: Castle
1f3f0.description: A castle, in a style that can be found in France and other parts of Europe. Castle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “European Castle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f492.title: Wedding
1f492.description: An emoji to depict a wedding, displayed by most vendors as a Christian church and love hearts. Some platforms display a cross or bell on the building. Wedding was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5fc.title: Tokyo Tower
1f5fc.description: The Tokyo Tower is the second-tallest building in Japan, located in Minato, Tokyo. Built in 1957, the design of the Tokyo Tower  was inspired by the Eiffel Tower in Paris, France and may be confused for it due to the small size of the emoji. Tokyo Tower was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5fd.title: Statue of Liberty
1f5fd.description: The Statue of Liberty, often used as a depiction of New York City. Statue of Liberty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26ea.title: Church
26ea.description: A church building, generally associated with Christian denominations. In addition quiet prayer, churches hold regular worship services, weddings, baptisms and funerals. Church was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f54c.title: Mosque
1f54c.description: A mosque building, a place of worship for followes of Islam. Shown with a domed roof and a minaret. Mosque was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f54d.title: Synagogue
1f54d.description: A synague; a place of worship for followers of Judaism. Displayed with a Star of David on the front. Synagogue was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26e9-fe0f.title: Shinto Shrine
26e9-fe0f.description: A shrine used for the Japanese Shinto religion. This emoji generally displays the torii, which is the gate to the Shinto Shrine. The torii is generally a red colored structure, with a curved roof section above two posts. This icon is used on maps in Japan to represent the location of a Shinto Shrine, similar to how the hot springs emoji is the icon used on Japanese maps to show the location of an onsen. Shinto Shrine was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f54b.title: Kaaba
1f54b.description: A cube-shaped building located at the centre of the Al-Masjid al-Haram Mosque in Mecca. Kaaba was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26f2.title: Fountain
26f2.description: A water fountain, found in a park or other public space. Used for decorative purposes. A variety of styles of fountain are shown across different platforms. Fountain was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26fa.title: Tent
26fa.description: A tent, used for protection from wind and rain when camping. Often shown at night time, under stars. Tent was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f301.title: Foggy
1f301.description: Foggy weather displayed as fog covering a bridge or cityscape, depending on the platform. For platforms that show a bridge, the red Golden Gate Bridge is generally displayed. Foggy was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f303.title: Night With Stars
1f303.description: A night sky with stars, depicted on major platforms as a cityscape at night. Night With Stars was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3d9-fe0f.title: Cityscape
1f3d9-fe0f.description: Cityscape was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f304.title: Sunrise Over Mountains
1f304.description: The sun rising over a mountain range, early in the morning. Sunrise Over Mountains was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f305.title: Sunrise
1f305.description: A sun rising, early in the morning. Can be difficult to distinguish from a sunset in some versions of this artwork. Sunrise was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f306.title: Cityscape at Dusk
1f306.description: A view of city buildings as the last light disappears from the sky. An orange (or blue) glow lingers, before the stars of the night sky become visible. Cityscape at Dusk was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f307.title: Sunset
1f307.description: A beautiful view, featuring an orange sky, with the sun setting over the buildings of a city skyline. Sunset was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Sunset Over Buildings” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f309.title: Bridge at Night
1f309.description: A lit-up bridge, shown at night. Bridge at Night was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2668-fe0f.title: Hot Springs
2668-fe0f.description: Representation of hot springs with steam rising from a circular tub. This is the common symbol used to represent an onsen on maps in Japan. Hot Springs was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3a0.title: Carousel Horse
1f3a0.description: A wooden painted horse, found on the carousel at a carnival. Faces to the left-of screen. A previous version of Windows displayed the carousel horse facing right, which was changed to face left on Windows 10 for cross-platform consistency. Carousel Horse was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3a1.title: Ferris Wheel
1f3a1.description: A large rotating wheel, often found at a carnival or fair. Ferris Wheel was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3a2.title: Roller Coaster
1f3a2.description: A roller coaster in a theme park going down a dip in the ride. Three carriages can be seen with two people in each red carriage. Roller Coaster was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f488.title: Barber Pole
1f488.description: A pole spiraled with red, white, and blue stripes, as spins out front of a barbershop. Commonly used for various content concerning haircutting and hairstyling. May also be associated with brothels in parts of Asia. Barber Pole was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3aa.title: Circus Tent
1f3aa.description: A circular ‘big top’ circus tent, with a triangle flag on top. Circus Tent was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f682.title: Locomotive
1f682.description: A steam train, powered by coal or wood. An early type of locomotive, now mostly replaced by electric or diesel trains. Oddly, this emoji does not show any steam coming from the train. Locomotive was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Steam Locomotive” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f683.title: Railway Car
1f683.description: A railway (railroad) car (carriage) that is generally pulled along a railway line by a locomotive. Shown with a pantograph above the carriage on many platforms which makes it look more like a tram car. Google’s artwork previously looked like a bus and Microsoft's older versions appeared similar to a minecart. Railway Car was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f684.title: High-Speed Train
1f684.description: A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed. High-Speed Train was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f685.title: Bullet Train
1f685.description: A high speed train, designed to cover long distances at high speed. Also features a streamlined bullet nose, often used in reference to the Shinkansen in Japan. Bullet Train was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “High-Speed Train With Bullet Nose” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f686.title: Train
1f686.description: A train, of no specified type. Due to the presence of a steam train and fast train emoji, this is likely to be a regular electrified or diesel passenger train. Train was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f687.title: Metro
1f687.description: A metro: frequent underground train found in built-up areas with high populations. This emoji is generally displayed as a forward-facing train, with some platforms also displaying a tunnel as a circle surrounding the train. Apple's artwork shows the characters IL2 which may be a reference to one of the more locked-down buildings at Apple's Infinite Loop Headquarters during iPhone development (IL2 = Infinite Loop 2). Metro was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f688.title: Light Rail
1f688.description: A form of public transport similar to a tram, but running on a track or network separated from cars and other types of traffic. Difficult to discern from a train at small sizes. Light Rail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f689.title: Station
1f689.description: A station, presumed to be a train station. Displays a train alongside a platform, where passengers can board. Station was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f68a.title: Tram
1f68a.description: A form of public transport on rails, usually found on streets in cities or other urban areas. For short or medium-length journeys. Trams tend to be similar to light rail, with the difference being that they don’t tend to have their own dedicated tracks. This emoji is generally shown as the front of the tram, on tracks. The intended usage of this emoji, instead of the tram car emoji is not clear. Tram was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f69d.title: Monorail
1f69d.description: Similar to a train, but running on a single track. Monorails are often found at theme parks, or other tourist destinations. Monorail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f69e.title: Mountain Railway
1f69e.description: A train and railway in the mountains. Displayed as a funicular in Microsoft’s artwork, or a regular train on other platforms. Android displays this train front-facing, leaving a tunnel, which appears similarly to the metro emoji at small sizes. Mountain Railway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f68b.title: Tram Car
1f68b.description: A form of public transport on rails, usually found on streets in cities or other urban areas. For short or medium-length journeys. Trams tend to be similar to light rail, with the difference being that they don’t tend to have their own dedicated tracks. This emoji is generally shown as the side of the tram. The intended usage of this emoji, instead of the tram emoji is not clear. Tram Car was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f68c.title: Bus
1f68c.description: A bus used for public transport in cities and towns. Could also be used as a school bus. Bus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f68d.title: Oncoming Bus
1f68d.description: The front of a bus, showing the windscreen, as well as wing mirrors in some versions of this emoji. Oncoming Bus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f68e.title: Trolleybus
1f68e.description: A type of bus that uses overhead electrical wires for power. Appears similar to a cross between a bus and a tram car. Trolleybus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f690.title: Minibus
1f690.description: A small bus or minivan designed to carry fewer people than a full-sized bus. Displayed in white on most platforms (green on Facebook). Minibus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f691.title: Ambulance
1f691.description: An ambulance, used to transport patients between their home and the hospital. Ambulance was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f692.title: Fire Engine
1f692.description: A red fire truck, an essential part of emergency services along with a police car or ambulance. May be on the way to put out a fire. Fire Engine was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f693.title: Police Car
1f693.description: A police car, shown with an emergency light on the top. This emoji is displayed from the side, as opposed to the oncoming police car emoji, which is shown from the front. Police Car was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f694.title: Oncoming Police Car
1f694.description: A police car, shown with an emergency light on the top. This emoji is displayed from the front, as opposed to the police car emoji, which is shown from the side. Oncoming Police Car was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f695.title: Taxi
1f695.description: A yellow taxicab, iconically seen in New York City. Shown from the side, as opposed to the oncoming taxi emoji. Taxi was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f696.title: Oncoming Taxi
1f696.description: A yellow taxicab, iconically seen in New York City. Shown from the front, as opposed to the taxi emoji which displays the side of the vehicle. Oncoming Taxi was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f697.title: Automobile
1f697.description: A car shown from the side, facing right-to-left. Appears as a red car on most platforms (which goes faster), except on Android where this displays as a silver car (previously blue). Automobile was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f698.title: Oncoming Automobile
1f698.description: A car being shown from the front. The windscreen and hood (bonnet in British English) of the car can be seen facing forward. This car shows in red or blue on most platforms. Silver on Android. Oncoming Automobile was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f699.title: Sport Utility Vehicle
1f699.description: A vehicle used for recreation, which is generally understood to mean a campervan or motorhome. May have originally been intended to represent an SUV, based on most versions of this emoji featuring a large vehicle with a spare tyre on the back. Sport Utility Vehicle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Recreational Vehicle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f69a.title: Delivery Truck
1f69a.description: Delivery Truck was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f69b.title: Articulated Lorry
1f69b.description: Articulated Lorry was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f69c.title: Tractor
1f69c.description: A tractor, may be used by a farmer or other occupation on the land. Tractor was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3ce-fe0f.title: Racing Car
1f3ce-fe0f.description: A racing car which appears as a formula one vehicle or rally car on most platforms. Generally displayed in red. Apple's version of this emoji features the Swift (programming language) logo on the side. Racing Car was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3cd-fe0f.title: Motorcycle
1f3cd-fe0f.description: A motorcycle, otherwise known as a motorbike used for sport/racing purposes. For a transport-based motorcycle, use a motor scooter. Motorcycle was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Racing Motorcycle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6b2.title: Bicycle
1f6b2.description: A bicycle, sometimes called a push bike, used for transport or sport. Bicycle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f68f.title: Bus Stop
1f68f.description: A sign indicating the location of a bus stop by the side of a road. Some platforms display this as a red, white and blue sign which can be found in parts of Japan. This interpretation has a slight resemblance to the Pepsi Globe. Other platforms base this emoji design on bus stop signage of other regions. Bus Stop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6e3-fe0f.title: Motorway
1f6e3-fe0f.description: A wide road shown from a first person perspective. Apple's artwork displays a road sign to Curpertino. Motorway was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6e4-fe0f.title: Railway Track
1f6e4-fe0f.description: Railway Track was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6e2-fe0f.title: Oil Drum
1f6e2-fe0f.description: A barrel for transporting bulk liquids, such as oil. Generally depicted as a red or blue metal drum with holes or a stopper on its lid. Commonly used for various content concerning petroleum or hazardous waste. Google’s design displays a yellow oil drop symbol. Samsung's design previously featured a yellow hazard sign. Oil Drum was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26fd.title: Fuel Pump
26fd.description: A fuel pump, used to fill up a vehicle with gas / petrol. Shown as red or orange on most platforms. Apple's artwork shows a droplet icon and the numbers 00322 but previously displayed the letter G on the front. Fuel Pump was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a8.title: Police Car Light
1f6a8.description: A revolving red light seen on top of a police car. Often used in emergency circumstances in addition to a siren making a loud warning sound. Police Car Light was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Police Cars Revolving Light” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a5.title: Horizontal Traffic Light
1f6a5.description: A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections. Less common than the vertical traffic light. Similar in appearance to the traffic light controls in the upper-left of every OS X windows. Horizontal Traffic Light was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a6.title: Vertical Traffic Light
1f6a6.description: A set of red, orange (amber) and green traffic lights, used at intersections. More common than the horizontal traffic light. Vertical Traffic Light was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a7.title: Construction
1f6a7.description: A sign used to indicate roadwork or construction. Generally shown as yellow and black diagonal stripes, and often used to physically block access to a road or area. May be used to imply a website or project in progress or under construction. Construction was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Construction Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26f5.title: Sailboat
26f5.description: A sailboat, otherwise known as a sailing boat or yacht.  Uses wind as the source of propulsion to move around a body of water. The color of the sails in this emoji vary by platform, with vendors displaying blue sails, orange sails, or a mix of red, yellow, orange, blue or white. Sailboat was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a4.title: Speedboat
1f6a4.description: A motorized speedboat used for recreation on lakes, or other bodies of water. Speedboat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6f3-fe0f.title: Passenger Ship
1f6f3-fe0f.description: Passenger Ship was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26f4-fe0f.title: Ferry
26f4-fe0f.description: Ferry was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6e5-fe0f.title: Motor Boat
1f6e5-fe0f.description: Motor Boat was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a2.title: Ship
1f6a2.description: A large ship, used for transport of people or cargo across the ocean. May be a cruise ship, commonly found around tropical locations. Ship was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2708-fe0f.title: Airplane
2708-fe0f.description: Used either as a literal airplane, or sometimes to represent an overseas vacation, or airplane mode on a phone or tablet. As of July 2018 the airplane emoji has been made available as a new Facebook reaction for users in some markets. This is available in addition to existing emoji reactions such as the thumbs up, heart, or laughing face and appears to be the unintentially result of a internal testing reaction being made public. Airplane was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6e9-fe0f.title: Small Airplane
1f6e9-fe0f.description: A light aircraft which is shown with propellers on some platforms. Small Airplane was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6eb.title: Airplane Departure
1f6eb.description: A plane taking off from a runway. Generally displayed left-right, with the front of the plane elevated. Airplane Departure was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6ec.title: Airplane Arrival
1f6ec.description: A plane approaching a runway for landing. Generally displayed left-right, with the front of the plane facing toward the ground in a position that may result in a crash if attempted in the real world. Airplane Arrival was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Airplane Arriving” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4ba.title: Seat
1f4ba.description: A seat, which could refer to any form of place to sit, with the distinction that a seat is generally fixed, and is not a chair which can be moved. This emoji is intended to be a seat on some form of mass-transit, such as on an airplane, train or bus. Google previously displayed this as an orange wooden chair. Seat was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f681.title: Helicopter
1f681.description: A helicopter, which can hover in the air. Often seen in emergency circumstances such as transporting patients to a hospital, or for police or fire-fighting activity. Helicopter was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f69f.title: Suspension Railway
1f69f.description: Similar to a monorail, a suspension railway is elevated, but the vehicle is suspended under the track. Suspension Railway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a0.title: Mountain Cableway
1f6a0.description: Mountain Cableway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a1.title: Aerial Tramway
1f6a1.description: An Aerial Tramway, most commonly seen at ski resorts, for transport between locations on a mountain. Can also be used as a tourist attraction, or as a form of public transport. Aerial Tramway was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6f0-fe0f.title: Satellite
1f6f0-fe0f.description: A satellite which orbits the earth, and is generally used for communications, weather, and GPS. Satellite was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f680.title: Rocket
1f680.description: A rocket being propelled into space. Rocket was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6ce-fe0f.title: Bellhop Bell
1f6ce-fe0f.description: Ding! A call bell, as pressed at a front desk or reception to alert staff for service, such as from a concierge or bellhop (porter) to carry luggage at a hotel. Generally depicted as a golden bell on a wooden stand. Commonly represents alerts or notifications to bring attention to important content. May also be used of various content concerning the hospitality and service industries. Microsoft’s design features a silver bell radiating yellow rays, as if ringing. Bellhop Bell was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

231b.title: Hourglass Done
231b.description: A classic hourglass, all of its sand having flowed into the bottom bulb. Indicates time has passed. Color varies across platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also be used for hourglass-shaped figures. Not to be confused with ⏳ Hourglass Not Done, whose sand is still flowing. Used on Snapchat to indicate a Snapstreak is soon to end. Hourglass Done was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Hourglass” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23f3.title: Hourglass Not Done
23f3.description: A classic hourglass, its sand still flowing from the top to bottom bulb. Indicates time is still passing—but life is short. Color varies across platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also be used for hourglass-shaped figures. Not to be confused with ⌛ Hourglass Done, whose sand has stopped flowing. Hourglass Not Done was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Hourglass With Flowing Sand” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

231a.title: Watch
231a.description: A wristwatch, as used for telling time. Appearance varies across platforms, but widely depicted as an analog timepiece with a white face and brown or black straps. Used for various content concerning time, including watches as accessories. Apple's design is an Apple Watch, though previously featured a traditional watch before the product’s release. Watch was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23f0.title: Alarm Clock
23f0.description: A timepiece set in advance to startle a person awake at the designated time with its two bells. That is, before hitting snooze. Appearance varies across platforms, but depicted as a classic, wind-up, bedside alarm clock, often red in color. May be used for various content concerning alarms, alerts, sleeping, waking, and time more generally. Alarm Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23f1-fe0f.title: Stopwatch
23f1-fe0f.description: An analog, handheld timepiece used to measure elapsed time, as for athletic sprints. Appearance varies across platforms, but depicted with two or more control buttons on its top. Used for various content concerning time. Not to be confused with ⏰ Alarm Clock or other clock emojis. Stopwatch was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23f2-fe0f.title: Timer Clock
23f2-fe0f.description: Time’s up! A timer set to count down and sound an alarm after a designated amount of time, as used in the kitchen. Appearance varies by platform. Commonly used for various content concerning time, including countdowns and deadlines. Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s designs resemble kitchen timers. Other designs may be confused with 🕰️ Mantelpiece Clock or other clock emojis. Timer Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f570-fe0f.title: Mantelpiece Clock
1f570-fe0f.description: An antique-styled mantel clock with a flat base and rounded case, as made of wood and brass and placed above a fireplace. Commonly used for various content concerning time. May also suggest a traditional home or old-time environment. Samsung’s design features a more modern-looking, blue clock. Mantelpiece Clock was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f55b.title: Twelve O’Clock
1f55b.description: Twelve O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Twelve O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f567.title: Twelve-Thirty
1f567.description: Twelve-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Twelve-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f550.title: One O’Clock
1f550.description: One O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face One O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f55c.title: One-Thirty
1f55c.description: One-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face One-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f551.title: Two O’Clock
1f551.description: Two O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Two O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f55d.title: Two-Thirty
1f55d.description: Two-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Two-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f552.title: Three O’Clock
1f552.description: Three O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Three O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f55e.title: Three-Thirty
1f55e.description: Three-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Three-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f553.title: Four O’Clock
1f553.description: Four O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Four O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f55f.title: Four-Thirty
1f55f.description: Four-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Four-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f554.title: Five O’Clock
1f554.description: Five O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Five O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f560.title: Five-Thirty
1f560.description: Five-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Five-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f555.title: Six O’Clock
1f555.description: Six O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Six O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f561.title: Six-Thirty
1f561.description: Six-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Six-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f556.title: Seven O’Clock
1f556.description: Seven O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Seven O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f562.title: Seven-Thirty
1f562.description: Seven-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Seven-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f557.title: Eight O’Clock
1f557.description: Eight O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Eight O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f563.title: Eight-Thirty
1f563.description: Eight-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Eight-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f558.title: Nine O’Clock
1f558.description: Nine O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Nine O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f564.title: Nine-Thirty
1f564.description: Nine-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Nine-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f559.title: Ten O’Clock
1f559.description: Ten O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Ten O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f565.title: Ten-Thirty
1f565.description: Ten-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Ten-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f55a.title: Eleven O’Clock
1f55a.description: Eleven O’Clock was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Eleven O’Clock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f566.title: Eleven-Thirty
1f566.description: Eleven-Thirty was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clock Face Eleven-Thirty” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f311.title: New Moon
1f311.description: A new moon, the first of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a full, bluish- or grayish-black, cratered disc, not illuminated by the sun. May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. See also 🌚 New Moon Face. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme. Google’s new moon was previously a gray circle with a yellow outline. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a new moon in a night sky with stars. New Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “New Moon Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f312.title: Waxing Crescent Moon
1f312.description: A waxing crescent moon (appearing to become larger), the second of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its right side illuminated in a thin, golden or silver crescent, its remainder dark. May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. See also 🌙 Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with 🌘 Waning Crescent Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a crescent moon in a night sky with stars. Waxing Crescent Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Waxing Crescent Moon Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f313.title: First Quarter Moon
1f313.description: A first quarter moon, the third of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its right half illuminated in gold or silver, its remainder dark. May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. See also 🌛 First Quarter Moon Face. Not to be confused with 🌗 Last Quarter Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a first quarter moon in a night sky with stars. First Quarter Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “First Quarter Moon Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f314.title: Waxing Gibbous Moon
1f314.description: A waxing gibbous moon (appearing more than half full and getting larger), the fourth of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, mostly illuminated in gold or silver, but with its left side a dark crescent. May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. Not to be confused with 🌖 Waning Gibbous Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning gibbous moon in a night sky with stars. Waxing Gibbous Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Waxing Gibbous Moon Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f315.title: Full Moon
1f315.description: A full moon, the fifth phase of the eight phases of the moon, when it is completely lit. Depicts the moon as a full, gold or silver, cratered disc, completely illuminated by the sun. May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. Commonly used during Halloween, associated with werewolves and Friday the 13th. See also 🌝 Full Moon Face. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a full moon in a night sky with stars. Full Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Full Moon Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f316.title: Waning Gibbous Moon
1f316.description: A waning gibbous moon (appearing more than half full but getting smaller), the sixth of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, mostly illuminated in gold or silver, but with its right side a dark crescent. May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. Not to be confused with 🌔 Waxing Gibbous Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning gibbous moon in a night sky with stars. Waning Gibbous Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Waning Gibbous Moon Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f317.title: Last Quarter Moon
1f317.description: A last quarter moon, the seventh of the eight phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its left side half illuminated in gold or silver, its remainder dark. May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. See also 🌜 Last Quarter Moon Face. Not to be confused with 🌓 First Quarter Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a last quarter moon in a night sky with stars. Last Quarter Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Last Quarter Moon Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f318.title: Waning Crescent Moon
1f318.description: A waning crescent moon (appearing to become smaller), the last of the phases of the moon. Depicts the moon as a cratered disc, its left side illuminated in a thin, golden or silver crescent, its remainder dark. May be used to represent the moon more generally, nighttime, outer space, and astronomy. May also be used to convey enchanting or eerie feelings. See also 🌙 Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with 🌒 Waxing Crescent Moon, though their applications may overlap. Used as part of the Moon Emoji Creep meme. Samsung’s design once resembled a full moon with stars and previously displayed as a waning crescent moon in a night sky with stars. Waning Crescent Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Waning Crescent Moon Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f319.title: Crescent Moon
1f319.description: A crescent moon, as in its waxing crescent phase. Depicts the moon as a thin, golden crescent, curving to the right and not displaying the remaining outline of the moon. May be used for the moon more generally and saying good night. May be used in association with ☪️ Star and Crescent, a popular but unofficial symbol of Islam. As of March 2019, sending this emoji over Facebook Messenger activates dark mode. See also 🌒 Waxing Crescent Moon. Google’s moon once resembled a waning crescent moon, Twitter and Facebook's moons were previously silver. Crescent Moon was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f31a.title: New Moon Face
1f31a.description: A new moon with a smiling face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts the moon as a dark disc with a slightly smiling human face and nose. See also 🌑 New Moon. May be used to represent the moon more generally. Popularly perceived as creepy, used to throw shade (express disapproval), or convey various suggestive or ironic sentiments. Apple and WhatsApp’s eyes are looking left, as if giving the side-eye. Samsung and Facebook’s faces are looking straight ahead. Google’s facial expression resembles 😏 Smirking Face, Twitter’s 🙂 Slightly Smiling Face. Google’s face previously evoked Lenny Face, Microsoft’s eyes appeared closed, and Facebook’s face was a simple smiley. New Moon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “New Moon With Face” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f31b.title: First Quarter Moon Face
1f31b.description: A first quarter moon with a human face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts a wide, golden crescent moon with the profile of a slightly smiling human face with a nose, facing left. May be used to represent the moon more generally and saying good night. See also 🌓 First Quarter Moon and 🌙 Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with 🌜 Last Quarter Moon Face, though their applications may overlap. WhatsApp’s eyes are looking back. Facebook’s moon is silver but was previously golden; Twitter’s was previously silver. Google’s eyes were previously closed. First Quarter Moon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “First Quarter Moon With Face” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f31c.title: Last Quarter Moon Face
1f31c.description: A last quarter moon with a human face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts a wide, golden crescent moon with the profile of slightly smiling human face with a nose, facing right. May be used to represent the moon more generally and saying good night. See also 🌗 Last Quarter Moon and 🌙 Crescent Moon. Not to be confused with 🌛 First Quarter Moon Face, though their applications may overlap. WhatsApp’s eyes are looking back. Facebook’s moon is silver but was previously golden; Twitter’s was previously silver. Google’s eyes were previously closed. Last Quarter Moon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Last Quarter Moon With Face” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f321-fe0f.title: Thermometer
1f321-fe0f.description: A liquid-in-glass thermometer, as used to measure temperature. Depicted at various angles with a red liquid risen from the bulb to various levels on the scale. Commonly used for content concerning high temperatures, including warm weather, illness (having a fever), and various slang senses of hot. Thermometer was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2600-fe0f.title: Sun
2600-fe0f.description: The sun, the star at the center of our solar system. Generally depicted as a golden-yellow disc radiating eight triangular rays, representing the sun’s heat and light. Commonly used to represent sunny, warm, or hot weather, light, heat, energy, life, outer space, astronomy, and various positive and happy (sunny) feelings. See also 🌞 Sun With Face. Not to be confused with 🔆 Bright Button or 🔅 Dim Button. Google’s sun was once red, Samsung’s previously gray. See the glossary for the term black in Unicode character names. Sun was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Black Sun With Rays” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f31d.title: Full Moon Face
1f31d.description: A full moon with a smiling face, as the Man in the Moon. Generally depicts the moon as a dark disc with a slightly smiling human face and nose. See also 🌕 Full Moon. May be used to represent the moon more generally. Commonly used a smiley. Occasionally used for irony and sarcasm. Apple and WhatsApp’s eyes are looking left, as if giving the side-eye. Samsung and Facebook’s faces are looking straight ahead. Google’s facial expression resembles 😏 Smirking Face, Twitter’s 🙂 Slightly Smiling Face. Google’s face previously evoked Lenny Face, Microsoft’s eyes appeared to be closed, Twitter’s resembled its 🌚 New Moon Face, and Facebook’s face was a simple, yellow smiley. Full Moon Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Full Moon With Face” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f31e.title: Sun With Face
1f31e.description: A sun with a smiling face, as a Sun of May. Generally depicted as a golden-yellow disc with a smiling, often human face with a nose, radiating triangular rays, representing the sun's heat and light. May be used to represent the sun more generally. Also used to represent sunny, warm, or hot weather and various positive and happy (sunny) feelings. See also ☀️ Sun. Not to be confused with 🔆 Bright Button or 🔅 Dim Button. Apple, WhatsApp, and Facebook's suns feature human faces. Other platforms, including Twitter, feature a simple smiley, as 🙂 Slightly Smiling Face. Microsoft's eyes previously appeared closed, Facebook's expression resembled 😁 Beaming Face With Smiling Eyes. Sun With Face was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2b50.title: Star
2b50.description: A classic, five-point gold star. Commonly used for various metaphorical senses of star (e.g., for fame, success, excellence, reviews). Also used for emphasis or flair. Occasionally used for astronomical stars. Not to be confused with 💫 Dizzy, 🌟 Glowing Star, 🌠 Shooting Star, or ✨ Sparkles, though their applications may overlap. Samsung and Facebook’s stars were once silver. See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names. Star was approved as part of Unicode 5.1 in 2008 under the name “White Medium Star” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f31f.title: Glowing Star
1f31f.description: A glowing, five-point gold star. Depicted as ⭐ Star with stylized bursts in between its points, representing glowing or twinkling. Commonly used to represent various senses of glowing as well for as for a sense of flourish. Not to be confused with 💫 Dizzy, ⭐ Star, 🌠 Shooting Star, or ✨ Sparkles, though their applications may overlap. On Snapchat, this emoji displays next to a contact who has had their snaps replayed in the past 24 hours. Microsoft’s bursts are blue lines, though were previously yellow. Apple’s star previously resembled its ⭐ Star. Samsung’s star previously displayed a burst radiating out from its center. Glowing Star was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f320.title: Shooting Star
aliases: When You Wish Upon A Star
1f320.description: A stylized representation of a shooting star, a small, fast meteor that burns up in the atmosphere. Generally depicted as a gold, five-point star trailing yellow motion lines against a night sky, as if moving down to the left. May be used for astronomical stars and other content concerning space. Also may be used for flair or flourish. Sometimes used as a visual reference to NBC’s More You Know public service announcement, popular in the 1990s and featuring a shooting star logo. Not to be confused with 💫 Dizzy, ⭐ Star, 🌟 Glowing Star, or ✨ Sparkles, though their applications may overlap. Google’s star is trailed, without backdrop, by yellow lines, though they were previously blue. Microsoft’s star is trailed, without backdrop, by blue lines, though they were previously yellow. Shooting Star was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f30c.title: Milky Way
1f30c.description: The Milky Way – a galaxy of billions of stars that includes our own solar system and planet earth. Shown by many platforms as a night sky, with silhouettes of mountains or hills in the foreground. Milky Way was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2601-fe0f.title: Cloud
2601-fe0f.description: A fluffy, white cloud, as a cumulus. May be used as a weather icon to represent a cloudy or overcast day. Google’s cloud is bluish, Twitter’s design features two clouds. Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26c5.title: Sun Behind Cloud
26c5.description: A yellow sun half covered by a white cloud. Position of the sun varies across platforms. May be used as a weather icon to represent a partly cloudy day. Not to be confused with 🌤️ Sun Behind Small Cloud or ⛅ Sun Behind Large Cloud, though their applications may overlap. Microsoft’s cloud was previously gray, Samsung’s bluish. Sun Behind Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26c8-fe0f.title: Cloud With Lightning and Rain
26c8-fe0f.description: Blue raindrops falling from a white cloud with a lightning bolt flashing. May be used as a weather icon to represent thundershowers. Not to be confused with 🌩️ Cloud With Lightning, though their applications may overlap. Cloud With Lightning and Rain was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 under the name “Thunder Cloud and Rain” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f324-fe0f.title: Sun Behind Small Cloud
1f324-fe0f.description: A yellow sun partially covered by a small, white cloud. Position of the cloud varies across platforms. May be used as a weather icon to represent a mostly sunny day. Not to be confused with ⛅ Sun Behind Cloud or 🌥️ Sun Behind Large Cloud, though their applications may overlap. See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names. Sun Behind Small Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “White Sun With Small Cloud” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f325-fe0f.title: Sun Behind Large Cloud
1f325-fe0f.description: A yellow sun mostly covered by a large, white cloud. Position of the sun varies across platforms. May be used as a weather icon to represent a mostly cloudy day. Not to be confused with ⛅ Sun Behind Cloud or 🌤️ Sun Behind Small Cloud, though their applications may overlap. Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish. See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names. Sun Behind Large Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “White Sun Behind Cloud” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f326-fe0f.title: Sun Behind Rain Cloud
aliases: White Sun Behind Cloud With Rain
1f326-fe0f.description: A yellow sun half covered by a white rain cloud with blue raindrops. Most platforms depict the raindrops falling to the left. Position of the sun varies across platforms. May be used as a weather icon to represent a mix of sunshine and scattered showers. Not to be confused with ⛅ Sun Behind Cloud. Samsung’s cloud was previously bluish. See the glossary for the term white in Unicode character names. Sun Behind Rain Cloud was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “White Sun Behind Cloud With Rain” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f327-fe0f.title: Cloud With Rain
1f327-fe0f.description: A rain cloud. (Keep dry with ☔ Umbrella With Rain Drops.) Depicted as blue raindrops falling from a white cloud. Most platforms depict the raindrops falling to the left.
