Its flight may represent losing, transferring, or earning money, but commonly used for wealth, money, and success more generally, often with a flourish or sense of flair. Money With Wings was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4b3.title: Credit Card
1f4b3.description: The backside of a credit card, showing the magnetic strip and signature. Color and detail vary across platforms, but often shown as gold, silver, or blue. May be used for banking and other ID cards as well for various content concerning money, including payment. Some vendors feature easter eggs: Apple’s design features John Appleseed in the signature and a security code of 448, and Samsung’s, the initials KJH and 856 658. Facebook’s design features founder Mark Zuckerberg’s signature and a security code of 123. Credit Card was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4b9.title: Chart Increasing With Yen
aliases: Chart With Upwards Trend and Yen Sign
1f4b9.description: A graph showing the current value of the Japanese Yen. Chart Increasing With Yen was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Chart With Upwards Trend and Yen Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4b1.title: Currency Exchange
1f4b1.description: A symbol for exchanging of two currencies. Most commonly displayed as a dollar symbol, with arrows to and from a yen symbol. Some platforms instead show banknotes and coins in yen, dollars, euros and pounds. Currency Exchange was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4b2.title: Heavy Dollar Sign
1f4b2.description: Heavy Dollar Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2709-fe0f.title: Envelope
2709-fe0f.description: The back of an envelope, as used to send a letter or card in the mail (post). Generally depicted in white, though Google’s design is yellow. Used for various content concerning mail and messages, including email. Samsung’s design previously featured a red, wax seal imprinted with the initial M. Envelope was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4e7.title: E-Mail
1f4e7.description: A symbol for email. Depicted as the back of an envelope imprinted with a capital letter E (for electronic) or @ (at) sign. Commonly used as an icon before an email address. The envelope is generally white (except for Google’s yellow design) and the E or @, blue. Apple and Google’s designs feature the letter E, Microsoft and Samsung’s the @ sign. E-Mail was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “E-Mail Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4e8.title: Incoming Envelope
1f4e8.description: The back of an envelope, shown coming into an inbox or arriving with motion lines. Commonly used as an icon for an email address. May also represent posting mail or sending messages more generally. Apple and WhatsApp’s designs include an inbox tray. Microsoft and Facebook’s designs feature a yellow envelope angled forward and trailed by three, blue lines, indicating sending. Apple’s design previously featured three red motion lines, Microsoft’s a right arrow. Incoming Envelope was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4e9.title: Envelope With Arrow
1f4e9.description: The back of envelope with a down arrow on top. Generally depicted in white (except for Google’s yellow design) with a red or blue arrow. Commonly used an icon before an email address. May also represent downloading, direct messages, or mail (post) more generally. Its original intent may have been to indicate sealing and delivering a letter in an envelope. Microsoft’s design previously resembled an incoming envelope. Early designs from Apple featured a right arrow with the envelope oriented lengthwise. SoftBank originally animated a rightward-moving arrow and envelope, suggesting sending or sent. Envelope With Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Envelope With Downwards Arrow Above” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4e4.title: Outbox Tray
1f4e4.description: A paper tray with an up arrow on top, as a symbol for an email outbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden tray with a red arrow. May be used for various digital activity, including uploading, messaging, emailing, ordering, and sharing. Google’s design features a blue arrow and contains paper, as does Facebook’s. Samsung’s arrow was previously green. Compare 📥 Inbox Tray. Outbox Tray was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4e5.title: Inbox Tray
1f4e5.description: A paper tray with a down arrow on top, as a symbol for an email inbox. Generally depicted as a white or wooden try with a red or green arrow. May be used for various digital activity, including downloading, messaging, and emailing. Google’s design feature a blue arrow and contains paper, as does Facebook's. See also 📤 Outbox Tray. Inbox Tray was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4e6.title: Package
1f4e6.description: A package (parcel), as contains items ordered online. Depicted at various angles as a light-brown, cardboard box, with a shipping label and its top taped shut. Commonly used for content concerning shipping, delivery, and moving as well as for boxes more generally. Apple’s design features an image of a wine glass, indicating fragile contents, and “this way up” orientation arrows. It was briefly identical to its 🎁 Wrapped Gift. Package was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4eb.title: Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag
1f4eb.description: A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag raised. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email. Indicates in the United States that incoming mail (post) has been delivered. May also indicate that there is outgoing mail for pickup. Compare 📪 Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, 📭 Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and 📬 Open Mailbox With Raised Flag. Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4ea.title: Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag
1f4ea.description: A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its door latched shut and signal flag lowered. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email. Indicates in the United States that no incoming mail (post) has been delivered. May also indicate that outgoing mail has been picked up. Compare 📫 Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, 📭 Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and 📬 Open Mailbox With Raised Flag. Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4ec.title: Open Mailbox With Raised Flag
1f4ec.description: An open, curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag raised and a letter in its open slot. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag and white envelope (Google's design is yellow). Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email. Indicates in the United States that there is outgoing mail (post) for pickup. May also indicate that incoming mail has been delivered. Compare 📫 Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, 📪 Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and 📭 Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag. Open Mailbox With Raised Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4ed.title: Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag
1f4ed.description: A curbside mailbox (letterbox, postbox) with its signal flag lowered and its slot empty. Generally depicted in blue or gray with a red flag. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email. Indicates in the United States that outgoing mail has been picked up. May also indicate that no incoming mail has been delivered. Compare 📫 Closed Mailbox With Raised Flag, 📪 Closed Mailbox With Lowered Flag, and 📬 Open Mailbox With Raised Flag. Open Mailbox With Lowered Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4ee.title: Postbox
1f4ee.description: A postbox (mailbox, letterbox) with a letter in its slot for collection. Generally depicted in red with a white envelope, styled after public postboxes in Japan. May also evoke postboxes in the United Kingdom. Used for various content concerning postal deliveries and email. Microsoft’s design is blue, after U.S. mail collection boxes. Postbox was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5f3-fe0f.title: Ballot Box With Ballot
1f5f3-fe0f.description: A ballot box, as used to cast votes in an election. Depicted as a box, generally blue or gray, with a slot on top through which a paper ballot is being inserted. Many platforms display a cross mark or check mark on the ballot to indicate a vote, though Apple and Facebook leave theirs blank. Commonly used for various content concerning voting and elections, especially in politics and government. Ballot Box With Ballot was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

270f-fe0f.title: Pencil
270f-fe0f.description: A classic yellow pencil. Depicted as a graphite pencil, like a U.S. #2 or European HB, with a sharpened tip and pink eraser. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and schooling. Samsung’s pencil was previously red, Google’s green. Pencil was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2712-fe0f.title: Black Nib
2712-fe0f.description: The silver nib of a fountain pen, which distributes ink onto a writing surface. Positioned at a 45° angle, with its tip at the lower left or right. Like 🖋️ Fountain Pen, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports). Several platforms, including Google, Microsoft, and Samsung, depict only a nib, sometimes ringed with gold. Other platforms, including Apple and Twitter, feature the same designs as their 🖋️ Fountain Pen, but with their tips angled to the lower right. Black Nib was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f58b-fe0f.title: Fountain Pen
1f58b-fe0f.description: A black fountain pen with a silver nib, as used for signing important documents. Often depicted with gold hardware. Positioned at a 45° angle with its tip at the lower left. Like ✒️ Black Nib, commonly used for various content concerning writing, drawing, and signing (e.g., laws, deals, in sports). Apple and Twitter feature the same designs as their ✒️ Black Nib, but with their tips angled to the lower left. Fountain Pen was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Lower Left Fountain Pen” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f58a-fe0f.title: Pen
1f58a-fe0f.description: A blue or black ballpoint pen, as used for everyday writing. Depicted with its cap removed onto its end or as retractable pen. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning writing (e.g., creative, professional) as well as signing (deals, laws, in sports). Google's design previously featured a brown-colored pen. Not to be confused with ✒️ Black Nib or 🖋️ Fountain Pen, though their applications often overlap. Pen was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Lower Left Ballpoint Pen” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f58c-fe0f.title: Paintbrush
1f58c-fe0f.description: A thin, artist's paintbrush, as used to paint a picture. Often depicted with reddish paint on its pointed bristles. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning the art of painting or fine art more generally. Often paired with 🎨 Artist Palette. Paintbrush was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Lower Left Paintbrush” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f58d-fe0f.title: Crayon
1f58d-fe0f.description: A crayon, as children use to color. Depicted as red on most platforms with two black stripes on its label, resembling a Crayola crayon. Positioned at a 45° angle, its tip at the lower left. Commonly used for various content concerning drawing, colors, arts and crafts, and schooling. WhatsApp’s crayon is green while Facebook’s is orange. Crayon was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Lower Left Crayon” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4dd.title: Memo
1f4dd.description: A white piece of paper with text written on it by a yellow pencil, positioned over the sheet, tip down, at a 45° angle. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, including signing (in sports). WhatsApp and Facebook’s designs depict an old-fashioned office memorandum on pink paper. Apple’s suggests an informal note with the easter egg of handwritten text from its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign: Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes… Not to be confused with 📄 Page Facing Up or other emojis featuring sheets of paper. Memo was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4bc.title: Briefcase
1f4bc.description: A place to store notes and other office materials. Primarily used by older people. Generally shown as a brown case with a handle on top, and a silver or gold colored clasp on the front. Facebook shows two leather straps on the front. Briefcase was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4c1.title: File Folder
1f4c1.description: A tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for a file on a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left. Commonly used for various content concerning filing, organization, and work, especially at an office. Apple’s folder is gray, Twitter’s is blue. Google’s design features multiple tabs, Microsoft’s a blue tab. Nearly identical in appearance and use to 📂 Open File Folder, which is slightly open. File Folder was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4c2.title: Open File Folder
1f4c2.description: A slightly open tabbed folder, as used to file papers in a cabinet or as an icon for an opened folder when using a computer. Most platforms depict a yellow folder, as manila, with the tab shown at the left. Commonly used for various content concerning filing, organization, and work, especially at an office. Apple’s folder is gray, Twitter’s is blue. Google’s design features multiple tabs, Microsoft’s a red tab. Nearly identical in appearance and use to 📁 File Folder, which is closed. Open File Folder was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5c2-fe0f.title: Card Index Dividers
1f5c2-fe0f.description: A set of tabbed dividers or file guides, as used to organize a card index or file box. Depicted with three or more multicolored tabs on manila paper. Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files, organization, and various types of data, information, and professional or academic work. WhatsApp’s design features tabbed index cards. Samsung’s design previously suggested a blue, multi-tabbed file folder. Card Index Dividers was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4c5.title: Calendar
1f4c5.description: A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page torn off from a daily desk calendar, displaying month (usually abbreviated and in a red or blue header) and day on a white, square page. Like 📆 Tear-Off Calendar and 🗓️ Spiral Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally. Apple, Google, Samsung, and JoyPixels's dates show July 17. Apple first featured this date in reference to its calendar app on July 17, 2002; originally known as iCal, the app's icon also displays July 17. Emojipedia so chose July 17 as the date for World Emoji Day, first celebrated in 2014. Several major platforms, including Google and Samsung, have since featured July 17 in honor of the occasion. Other vendors feature easter egg dates marking company founding or other milestones: Discontinued: Calendar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4c6.title: Tear-Off Calendar
1f4c6.description: A single date on a calendar. Generally depicted as a page on a two-ringed, daily desk calendar, as flipped or torn off to change the date. Displays month (usually abbreviated and in a red or blue header) and day on a white, square page, curled up at the bottom right. Like 📅 Calendar and 🗓️ Spiral Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally. Apple, Google, Samsung, and JoyPixels's dates show July 17. Apple first featured this date in reference to its calendar app on July 17, 2002; originally known as iCal, the app's icon also displays July 17. Emojipedia so chose July 17 as the date for World Emoji Day, first celebrated in 2014. Several major platforms, including Google and Samsung, have since featured July 17 in honor of the occasion. Other vendors feature easter egg dates marking company founding or other milestones: Discontinued: Tear-Off Calendar was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5d2-fe0f.title: Spiral Notepad
1f5d2-fe0f.description: A spiral-bound, flip-style notepad or notebook of lined paper, as used for everyday note-taking. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing. Most platforms depict a notepad opened to an empty, white page, sometimes shown curled at the bottom. Microsoft’s design is shown closed, with a yellow cover. Spiral Notepad was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Spiral Note Pad” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5d3-fe0f.title: Spiral Calendar
1f5d3-fe0f.description: A spiral-bound calendar. Generally depicted as a monthly calendar, with a red or blue header. Apple and Samsung’s pages are curled up at the bottom right, as to flip for a new month. Like 📅 Calendar and 📆 Tear-Off Calendar, commonly used as an icon for specific upcoming events or memorial dates. Also used for various content concerning time, date, schedules, planning, and observances and occasions more generally. Twitter and Facebook’s design feature a generic month, Microsoft’s a generic 31 (as the number of days in most months). WhatsApp's design shows in a green header February, when it was incorporated in 2009. Apple, Samsung, and JoyPixels’s designs show the month of July, when World Emoji Day falls on the 17th, a date Google specifically displays. Spiral Calendar was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Spiral Calendar Pad” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4c7.title: Card Index
1f4c7.description:
A card index, as a Rolodex, once used to organize and access cards containing the information of personal or business contacts. Depicted as a black or gray rotating device with a contact card displayed, including a graphic and text. Occasionally used to represent contact details/information and business cards. Thanks to its appearance, this emoji is sometimes mistaken for such things as documents or word processing. Apple’s design features a picture of its 👩 Woman, identified as Jane Appleseed (previously John Appleseed) with the following contact details as an easter egg: [email protected]
125 Main St.
City Name, CA 95014
Work: (408) 123-4567
Home: (400) 765-4321 95014 is the zip code (postcode) for Apple’s corporate headquarters in Cupertino, California. JoyPixels features its 👩‍⚕️ Woman Health Care Worker. WhatsApp's design also shows the picture of a woman. Card Index was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4c8.title: Chart Increasing
1f4c8.description: A graph showing a red or green trend line increasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of increase, from numerical data to being metaphorically on the rise. May also represent trending content as well as facts, figures, and charts more generally. Chart Increasing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Chart With Upwards Trend” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4c9.title: Chart Decreasing
1f4c9.description: A graph showing a colored trend line, often blue, decreasing over time, as stock prices or revenues. Commonly used to represent various types of decrease, from numeral data to being metaphorically down. May also represent facts, figures, and charts more generally. Google’s line is green, WhatsApp’s red, and Facebook’s orange. Chart Decreasing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Chart With Downwards Trend” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4ca.title: Bar Chart
1f4ca.description: A bar graph generally showing three different-colored, vertical rectangles at various heights, as compares values across a category. Commonly used to represent various types of data, information, facts, figures, and charts more generally. Several platforms, including Apple, depict (left to right) a green, red (lowest), and blue bar (highest). Google’s design includes four bars, with yellow the highest. Bar Chart was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4cb.title: Clipboard
1f4cb.description:
A white piece of paper secured by a silver clip on a brown clipboard, as used as a writing surface when standing. Commonly used for content concerning various types of documents and writing, especially in sports. Many platforms indicate text with dark lines. WhatsApp’s design shows lined paper. Facebook’s features the easter egg of a table with first names and numbers, perhaps as birthdates: Matt 3/28
Louie 4/30
Alexa 6/17
Brian 8/06 Apple’s design also features an easter egg, addressed Dear Katie and signed Take care from John Appleseed with the text of its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign: Here’s to the crazy ones. The misfits. The rebels. The troublemakers. The round pegs in the square holes. The ones who see things differently. They’re not fond of rules. You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them. About the only thing you can’t do is ignore them. Because they change things. They push the human race forward. And while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius. Because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do. Clipboard was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4cc.title: Pushpin
1f4cc.description: A thumbtack (drawing pin), as used to pin documents on a bulletin (notice) board. Depicted at a 45° angle with its red, flat head to the upper right. Often used as an icon for Pinterest or metaphorically pinning content online. Not to be confused with 📍 Round Pushpin, though their applications may overlap. Pushpin was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4cd.title: Round Pushpin
1f4cd.description: A pushpin, as used to indicate a location on a map. Generally depicted as an upright pin with a red, round head. Commonly used to indicate locations and notably featured in the Pushpin Emoji Detour and Distance Between memes on Twitter. Also used unofficially as an icon for Pinterest or Google Maps. Facebook’s pin is oriented at a 45° angle, as were previous designs on several other platforms. Not to be confused with 📌 Pushpin, though their applications may overlap. Round Pushpin was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4ce.title: Paperclip
1f4ce.description: A silver paper clip, as used to hold together sheets of paper—or remove a SIM card from a mobile phone. Shown positioned at various angles. Occasionally used to represent school/office supplies. Also sometimes used as an icon before a hyperlink. Not to be confused with 🔗 Link, 🖇️ Linked Paperclips, ⛓️ Chains, 🧷 Safety Pin—or Microsoft’s Clippy. Paperclip was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f587-fe0f.title: Linked Paperclips
1f587-fe0f.description: Two or more silver paper clips linked together, generally forming an inverted V. Microsoft’s design displays three paper clips. Occasionally used to represent school/office supplies or metaphorical connections. Also sometimes used as an icon before a hyperlink. Not to be confused with 🔗 Link or ⛓️ Chains. Linked Paperclips was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4cf.title: Straight Ruler
1f4cf.description: A ruler, as used to draw straight lines and measure distances. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic straightedge with length markings at a 45° angle. Commonly used for content concerning schooling, building, and measurement in various disciplines. May also represent various concepts of straightness and size. Straight Ruler was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4d0.title: Triangular Ruler
1f4d0.description: A triangle or set square, as used by engineers or architects to draw straight lines at angles. Variously depicted as a metal, wood, or plastic right triangle with length markings, its hypotenuse to the right. Commonly applied to a range of disciplines, including art, design, building, architecture, and STEM (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics). May also represent various concepts of angles and measurement. Triangular Ruler was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2702-fe0f.title: Scissors
2702-fe0f.description: A pair of scissors, as used to cut paper or hair. Generally shown open, blades down, with red handles. Commonly used for content concerning haircuts, fashion design, arts and crafts, and various senses of cutting. WhatsApp’s design features green handles with blades pointed up. See the glossary for the term black in Unicode character names. Scissors was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Black Scissors” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5c3-fe0f.title: Card File Box
1f5c3-fe0f.description: A black or gray box with a label holder, containing card index dividers with multicolored tabs, as used to organize and store files. Apple and Facebook’s designs include a lid. Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files, organization, and various types of data, information, and professional or academic work. Microsoft’s design previously resembled a shoebox. Card File Box was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5c4-fe0f.title: File Cabinet
1f5c4-fe0f.description: A metal filing cabinet, as used to organize and store file folders at an office. Depicted in black or gray with two drawers, handles, and label holders. Commonly used for various content concerning paper or computer files; filing and organization; various types of data, information, and archives; and office work. Google’s design was previously blue, Facebook’s had its bottom drawer open. File Cabinet was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5d1-fe0f.title: Wastebasket
1f5d1-fe0f.description: A wastebasket, as used to discard trash in an office. Generally depicted as a silver, wire-mesh container. Also known as a wastepaper basket, trash/garbage can, or rubbish bin. Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative waste. May also be used in the context of basketball. Sometimes paired with 🔥 Fire as a visual representation of the slang expression dumpster fire ("chatoic situation"). Samsung’s design depicts a metal can/bin with a lid, as used for outdoor garbage—or lived in by Oscar the Grouch. Not to be confused with 🧺 Basket. Wastebasket was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f512.title: Locked
1f512.description: A locked (closed) padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a secure internet connection, private account, or locked device. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle. WhatsApp’s design is silver. Commonly used for content concerning safety, security, privacy, and protection as well as various senses of lock, e.g., locked in/down. This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS). See also: 🔏 Locked With Pen and 🔐 Locked With Key. Locked was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Lock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f513.title: Unlocked
1f513.description: An unlocked padlock, as used to secure a latch or chain, or as an icon for a non-secure connection or open access online. Generally depicted with a gold base and silver shackle, as an open 🔒 Locked. May be used to represent a lack of or concerns about privacy and security. May also be used for figurative senses of unlocking, e.g., achievement unlocked. WhatsApp’s design is silver, its shackle turned to the right, as Samsung’s previously was. This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS). Unlocked was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Open Lock” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f50f.title: Locked With Pen
1f50f.description: A locked (closed) padlock with a fountain pen or nib positioned at various angles in front of it. Vendors implement the same design as their 🔒 Locked and the same or similar design as their 🖋️ Fountain Pen or ✒️ Black Nib. May represent digital certificates in public-key technology. May also have similar applications as 🔒 Locked (privacy, security) and 🖋️ Fountain Pen or ✒️ Black Nib (writing, signing). Apple’s design previously displayed a nib, Google’s a full pen. This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS). Locked With Pen was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Lock With Ink Pen” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f510.title: Locked With Key
1f510.description: A locked (closed) padlock with an upright key at its right. Vendors implement the same designs as their 🔒 Locked and 🔑 Key. May represent digital keys in public-key technology. May have similar applications as 🔒 Locked (privacy, security) and 🔑 Key (means of access, "crucial"). Sometimes used to represent a locket to symbolize romantic love and commitment. Apple’s design previously featured the easter egg UM242 on its key, a reference to locks on Herman Miller office furniture. Facebook’s design once displayed a silver key, its head at the bottom. This emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS). Locked With Key was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Closed Lock With Key” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f511.title: Key
1f511.description: A key, as opens a door or lock. Depicted at a 45° angle as a gold, bronze, or copper key with a round head and notched blade. Commonly used for figurative senses of key, e.g., the key to success, being key ("crucial"). DJ Khaled uses the emoji to indicate his Snapchat stories are official (verified). Apple’s design previously resembled a gold 🗝️ Old Key, which emoji has similar applications. May also represent digital keys in public-key technology. This may explain why the emoji does not display in page titles on Apple’s Safari web browser, presumably to prevent less reputable sites from pretending to be secure (encrypted using HTTPS). Key was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5dd-fe0f.title: Old Key
1f5dd-fe0f.description: An old-fashioned key, as opens an antique chest or wardrobe. Generally depicted at a 45° angle as a tarnished, silver skeleton key with an ornate, bowed head and two-toothed bit at the bottom left. Like 🔑 Key, often used figuratively, e.g., the key to success, being key ("crucial"). May also be applied to antiques. Microsoft’s design is gold, with the head at the upper left. Samsung and Facebook’s keys were previously gold. Old Key was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f528.title: Hammer
1f528.description: A claw hammer, as used for driving or removing nails. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left. Commonly used for content concerning tools, building, and construction as well as various senses of breaking or smashing. May also represent hard work or be applied to hammer-related expressions, e.g., nailed it. Apple and Facebook’s designs previously displayed a gavel, Softbank’s a mallet. Not to be confused with ⛏️ Pick or Axe. Hammer was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26cf-fe0f.title: Pick
26cf-fe0f.description: A pickaxe, a tool with a curved spike for breaking up rocks in mining. Generally depicted with a metal head and wooden handle, positioned at a 45° angle with the head at the upper left. May be used for various content concerning building, construction, digging, mining, or rock climbing. Not to be confused with 🔨 Hammer or Axe. Pick was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2692-fe0f.title: Hammer and Pick
2692-fe0f.description: A hammer and pick, as used for breaking up rocks in mining, crossed in an X shape. Generally depicted as metal, mallet- and chisel-styled hammers with wooden handles. The heads of the tools face up, with the pick usually at the right. Often used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction. Facebook implements the same designs as for its 🔨 Hammer and ⛏️ Pick. Samsung’s design previously featured stylized, white tools on a green square, as a sign or icon of a mine. Hammer and Pick was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6e0-fe0f.title: Hammer and Wrench
1f6e0-fe0f.description: A hammer and wrench, as kept in a toolbox, crossed in an X shape. Depicted with metal tools facing up, the hammer positioned at the upper left. Most vendors implement the same design as for their 🔨 Hammer and 🔧 Wrench. Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, construction, and work, both manual and digital. Hammer and Wrench was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5e1-fe0f.title: Dagger
1f5e1-fe0f.description: A pointed knife with a steel blade, as used for thrusting in close combat. Generally depicted as double-edged with a brown or black, cross-shaped hilt and positioned at 45° angle, often with its tip at the lower left. May represent knives and other bladed weapons (cf. ⚔️ Crossed Swords) as well as various senses of cutting and stabbing. Often applied to medieval or fantasy content. Microsoft’s design features a golden handle. Google’s design, featuring an icy-blue blade and sparkles, suggests a dagger elves may wield in fantasy. May be paired with (or defended by) 🛡️ Shield. Not to be confused with 🔪 Kitchen Knife. Dagger was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Dagger Knife” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2694-fe0f.title: Crossed Swords
2694-fe0f.description: Two swords with steel blades in an X shape, as crossed for combat between two knights or warriors. Generally depicted as straight, double-edged blades with brown or black, cross-shaped hilts, points directed up. Commonly used as a symbol for battle, fighting, or a contest, as in sports. Sometimes shown with golden handles. Several vendors implement the same design as for their 🗡️ Dagger. Samsung’s design previously featured stylized, white swords on a green square, as a sign or icon of war. May be paired with (or defended by) 🛡️ Shield. Not to be confused with ⚒️ Hammer and Pick or 🛠️ Hammer and Wrench. Crossed Swords was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f52b.title: Pistol
1f52b.description: A squirt gun (water pistol), as used to spray water for fun. On major platforms, depicted as a green or orange toy gun with an orange tip and barrel pointed left. Google, Microsoft, and Facebook’s designs include mounted reservoirs. Originally depicted as a classic handgun, as a revolver or other pistol. In 2016, Apple switched its design from weapon to toy; other major vendors followed suit by 2018. Deprecated emoji sets or smaller platforms still display the emoji as a handgun. Microsoft initially displayed the emoji as a toy ray gun before switching to a revolver, then squirt gun. Google once featured a blunderbuss. Pistol was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3f9.title: Bow and Arrow
1f3f9.description: A bow and arrow used in the sport of archery. May also be used by cupid. Bow and Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6e1-fe0f.title: Shield
1f6e1-fe0f.description: A shield, as blocks swords in close combat. Color and style varies across platforms, but generally depicted in a kite shape with a metal border and simple pattern. Commonly used to represent various content concerning battle, defense, security, and protection. Apple and Microsoft’s designs feature a red and white sawtooth pattern, Facebook and WhatsApp’s blue and white checkers. May be paired with (or fending off) ⚔️ Crossed Swords or 🗡️ Dagger. Not to be confused with 🔰 Japanese Symbol for Beginner. Shield was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f527.title: Wrench
1f527.description: A metal wrench (spanner), as used for turning nuts and bolts. Depicted with two open, crescent-shaped ends or one open end and a closed, ring-shaped end. Generally positioned at a 45° angle. Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, maintenance, and skilled trades like car mechanics and plumbing. Wrench was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f529.title: Nut and Bolt
1f529.description: A metal bolt with a nut threaded around it, as by a wrench. Often positioned at a 45° angle, the head of the bolt at the upper left. Commonly used for various content concerning tools, building, and construction. May also be used for other hardware, including screws. Apple’s bolt previously resembled a screw, Google’s a dumbbell; Microsoft’s design previously featured the nut and bolt separately. Nut and Bolt was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2699-fe0f.title: Gear
2699-fe0f.description: A toothed, wheel-shaped metal gear, as rotates to power machines. Commonly used for content concerning tools, equipment, and technology in a range of contexts, such as engineering, motor vehicles, and video games. May also represent hard work, e.g., grinding in sports. Samsung’s design features a stylized, white gear on a green square, as a sign or icon of machinery. Gear was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5dc-fe0f.title: Clamp
1f5dc-fe0f.description: A metal clamp or vice, as screwed to hold or compress materials like wood or metal. Depicted as a C-clamp or F-clamp, its screw in various positions. Commonly used for various content concerning tools, equipment, and technology. May also represent file compression in computer science. An image of a clamp, for example, is featured in the WinZip icon. Twitter’s clamp is red. Samsung’s design previously featured a clamp around a cardboard box. Clamp was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Compression” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2696-fe0f.title: Balance Scale
2696-fe0f.description: A balance scale, as historically used to measure weight. A symbol of justice, as held by Lady Justice, and of the zodiac sign of Libra, the Scales. Depicted as two silver or gold pans suspended from a beam and supported on a base. Commonly used for various content concerning law and justice as well as various senses of balance and weight. Samsung’s design previously featured a stylized, white balance scale on a green square, as an icon or symbol of legal matters or institutions. Balance Scale was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 under the name “Scales” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f517.title: Link
1f517.description: Two links of a silver chain, positioned at a 45° angle. Used as an icon for a hyperlink on computers and the internet. May also be used for metaphorical connections. Not to be confused with ⛓️Chains, 📎 Paperclip, 🖇️ Linked Paperclips, or 🧷 Safety Pin. Link was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Link Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26d3-fe0f.title: Chains
26d3-fe0f.description: Two parallel lengths of silver chain. Occasionally used as an icon before a hyperlink or for metaphorical connections or chains, e.g., slang off the chains. Samsung’s design previously featured stylized, white chains in a blue square, as a sign or icon for snow chains for winter driving. Not to be confused with 🔗 Link, 📎 Paperclip, 🖇️ Linked Paperclips, or 🧷 Safety Pin. Chains was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2697-fe0f.title: Alembic
2697-fe0f.description: An apparatus for distilling, as used in medieval alchemy. Generally depicted as a round flask with a neck angled down to the right. Positioned on a short stand and containing a mysterious green, purple, or blue liquid. Commonly used for various content concerning chemistry and science more generally. May represent various liquids, such as potions or medicines, as well as metaphorical laboratories and experiments. Thanks to the alembic’s association with alchemy, this emoji may also convey a sense of magic. And, thanks to its resemblance to a glass pipe, some use the emoji to represent a bong or other drug paraphernalia. Samsung’s design previously featured a copper still, as used for making whiskey. Alembic was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f52c.title: Microscope
1f52c.description: A microscope, as used in science laboratories to magnify small objects, such as cells or insects. Depicted as a compound opitical microscope with an adjustable eyepiece, lens, arm, and slide stage mounted on a base. Generally shown as metal with the viewing apparatus facing left. Commonly used for various content concerning science and research. May also be used for various senses of inspection (e.g., taking a closer took). Google’s design is shown in red. Microscope was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f52d.title: Telescope
1f52d.description: A telescope, as used to gaze at stars and planets in the night sky. Shown with an optical tube mounted on a tripod, positioned at various angles and generally depicted as metal. Commonly used for various content concerning astronomy, outer space, celestial objects, and science more generally. May also be used for various concepts of sight (e.g., spying, viewing). Google and Twitter’s designs feature red hardware. Telescope was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4e1.title: Satellite Antenna
1f4e1.description: A dish antenna, as used to send or receive information to or from a communication satellite—or 👽 Extraterrestrial Life. Generally depicted as a mounted, metal dish with its antenna positioned at 45° to the upper right. Commonly used to represent satellite television, radio, and internet, as well as broadcasting, streaming, cellular, and wireless services or technologies. May also represent various concepts of signals and transmission. Several platforms, including Samsung and Twitter, feature curved, radiating lines, as if transmitting data. Google’s design is depicted in blue. Satellite Antenna was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f489.title: Syringe
1f489.description: A medical syringe, as used to administer a shot or draw blood. Generally depicted at a 45° angle with a needle to the upper right, emitting two droplets of the red fluid in its barrel, as blood drawn for testing or donation at a hospital. Commonly used for content concerning health, medicine, and related professions as well as various senses of needles, drugs, and blood. Google and Facebook’s designs previously featured green liquids, Samsung’s syringe was empty. Syringe was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f48a.title: Pill
1f48a.description: A capsule of medicine. Generally depicted at a 45° angle, half red, half yellow. Commonly used for content concerning health, medicine, and related professions as well various types of drugs. Samsung’s design previously featured a blue-and-white capsule with two round pills, one orange, the other white. Google and Microsoft’s designs previously featured blue in their capsules. Pill was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6aa.title: Door
1f6aa.description: A door, as to the entrance of a room, house, or new opportunity. (We’ll see ourselves out 🚪🚶.) Depicted in brown, as made of wood, with a gold handle. May represent literal doors and related concepts (e.g., rooms, houses) but often used figuratively (e.g., opening or closing metaphorical doors). Google’s design features a peephole and Microsoft’s a step, as if a front door. Door was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6cf-fe0f.title: Bed
1f6cf-fe0f.description: A bed, made up for sleeping in a house, hotel, or other sleeping accommodation. Shown with a headboard at the left, footboard, mattress, pillow, and sheet. Most platforms suggest a wooden frame and feature blue or red sheets. Commonly used for various content concerning beds, furniture, and housing as well as sleeping, relaxing, and other bedroom activities. Vendors implement the same style of bed for 🛌 Person in Bed, but without a sleeper under the covers. Bed was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6cb-fe0f.title: Couch and Lamp
1f6cb-fe0f.description: A couch (sofa) with a floor lamp on the right, as in the living room of a house. Color and style of the couch and lamp vary widely by platform. Used for various content concerning furniture and housing as well as resting and lounging. Couch and Lamp was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6bd.title: Toilet
1f6bd.description: A white toilet, as used to deposit a 💩 Pile of Poo. (Don’t forget the 🧻 Roll of Paper.) Most platforms depict a porcelain toilet in profile, bowl facing to the left. Commonly used for various content concerning going to the bathroom or bathrooms more generally. May also be used figuratively, e.g., down the toilet. Google, Microsoft, and Twitter’s designs left the seat up. Toilet was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6bf.title: Shower
1f6bf.description: A silver shower head, streaming water to the left. Pressure level varies across platforms. 🧼 Soap not provided. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and water. Shower heads are also featured in 🛁 Bathtub and 🛀 Person Taking a Bath. Shower was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6c1.title: Bathtub
1f6c1.description: A white bathtub with a silver shower head. Often depicted as a cast-iron tub with claw-foot legs. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, cleaning, and bathrooms more generally. Several platforms, including Apple and Facebook, feature soap bubbles or suds. Samsung’s design displays streaming water from the shower head. Vendors implement 🛀 Person Taking a Bath with the same or a similar emoji, but with a person soaking in the tub. Bathtub was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6ac.title: Cigarette
1f6ac.description: A lit, filtered cigarette, shown burning at different directions. Commonly used to represent various forms of smoking (e.g., tobacco, marijuana, vaping) as well as metaphorical senses of smoking. Originally intended as a sign for a designated smoking area, as contrasted to 🚭 No Smoking Symbol. This is illustrated in Samsung’s previous design of a stylized, white cigarette on a blue background. Cigarette was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Smoking Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26b0-fe0f.title: Coffin
26b0-fe0f.description: A traditional coffin, as used to bury the dead. Depicted at various angles as a closed, six-sided, wooden coffin, tapered at the head and foot with golden handles. Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative death. May also be used for various content concerning funerals, horror, and Halloween. Apple and Microsoft’s designs place flowers on their lids. Coffin was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26b1-fe0f.title: Funeral Urn
26b1-fe0f.description: An urn, as used to hold the cremated ashes of the dead. Appearance varies, but generally depicted as a covered, bronze container with a rounded body and tapered foot. May be used for various content concerning death and funerals. May also be used for other types of vessels, such as pots or vases. Not to be confused with 🏺 Amphora. Funeral Urn was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f5ff.title: Moai
1f5ff.description: A moai, one of the famed, giant stone statues of human figures on Easter Island. Depicted as a gray stone carving of a stylized human head with a prominent brow and nose, most often facing left. Sometimes used for various idiosyncratic purposes, such as conveying a stoic, deadpan, or silly expression. Its official Unicode name of Moyai and inclusion in early Japanese emoji sets, such as from au by KDDI, suggest the emoji may represent the Moyai Statue near Shibuya Station in Tokyo, Japan; previous designs from Google and Microsoft resemble the Tokyo statue. Other Tokyo landmarks are represented in 🗼 Tokyo Tower and, formerly, Shibuya 109. Moai was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Moyai” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3e7.title: ATM Sign
1f3e7.description: ATM Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Automated Teller Machine” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6ae.title: Litter in Bin Sign
aliases: Put Litter in Its Place Symbol
1f6ae.description: A symbol showing a person putting litter (rubbish) in the trash (rubbish bin). A more positive version of the Do Not Litter Symbol. Litter in Bin Sign was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Put Litter in Its Place Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6b0.title: Potable Water
1f6b0.description: A symbol for potable (drinkable) water, usually shown with a faucet filling a drinking glass. Commonly used for various content concerning water, drinking, thirst, and dripping. Some platforms, including Apple and WhatsApp, depict the emoji as an object while others feature a stylized, white faucet on a blue square, as a sign or icon of water that is safe to drink. Compare 🚱 Non-Potable Water, which indicates water that is not safe to drink. Apple's design previously featured a blue symbol design, Microsoft's a cup filled with water. Potable Water was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Potable Water Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

267f.title: Wheelchair Symbol
267f.description: The international symbol of access, used to denote a facility which has been designed with accessibility or people in wheelchairs in mind. Appears as a blue sign, with a white graphic of a person sitting in a wheelchair. Many platforms now use the Accessible Icon Project style image for this emoji, which displays the person in the wheelchair in a more active position. Wheelchair Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6b9.title: Men’s Room
1f6b9.description: A stick-figure icon of a man, generally used to indicate a male restroom. The female equivalent is the Womens Symbol emoji. Men’s Room was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Mens Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6ba.title: Women’s Room
1f6ba.description: A stick-figure icon of a woman, generally used to indicate a female restroom. The male equivalent is the Mens Symbol emoji. Women’s Room was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Womens Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6bb.title: Restroom
1f6bb.description: A restroom symbol, depicting a iconography of a man and woman. Used to indicate the location of public bathrooms / toilets / restrooms. Used as an alternative to the water closet symbol. Restroom was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6bc.title: Baby Symbol
1f6bc.description: The symbol for a baby, usually used to indicate a room that is suitable to change a baby in. Often located in or near public restrooms. Baby Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6be.title: Water Closet
1f6be.description: A water closet is a name used for public toilet, bathroom or restroom used in some countries. Typically abbreviated to the letters WC, this may be found on signage in public buildings, as an alternative to the restroom symbol. Water Closet was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6c2.title: Passport Control
1f6c2.description: A person checking passports at an international border. Passport Control was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6c3.title: Customs
1f6c3.description: A customs officer inspecting luggage. May be shown on signage at airports or other border crossings. Not to be confused with the passport control emoji. Customs was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6c4.title: Baggage Claim
1f6c4.description: Baggage Claim was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6c5.title: Left Luggage
1f6c5.description: An icon representing a place to leave luggage. Most commonly found at Japanese train stations to signify coin lockers where bags can be stored for a daily fee. This emoji displays a suitcase with a key above or below it, ususually in blue. Left Luggage was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26a0-fe0f.title: Warning
26a0-fe0f.description: A triangle with an exclamation mark inside, used as a warning or alert. Warning was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 under the name “Warning Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6b8.title: Children Crossing
1f6b8.description: A crossing sign for children, usually positioned near schools or other areas that drivers should be cautious of young children in the area. Children Crossing was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26d4.title: No Entry
26d4.description: No Entry was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6ab.title: Prohibited
1f6ab.description: Called a “No Entry” sign Emoji, but does not look like the no entry road sign that one might expect. The artwork for this Emoji looks more like a restriction sign, as in No Smoking, No Bikes, or similar. Prohibited was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “No Entry Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6b3.title: No Bicycles
1f6b3.description: A bicycle with a red stroke through it, indicating that bikes are prohibited from this location. May be seen in pedestrian malls with a bicycle restriction or crossing train tracks in some countries. No Bicycles was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6ad.title: No Smoking
1f6ad.description: No Smoking was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “No Smoking Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6af.title: No Littering
1f6af.description: A person dropping litter (rubbish, trash) with a red stroke through it, indicating that littering is prohibited in this area. Usually implied by the fact that littering is not welcome anywhere, this sign serves as a reminder in areas that are known to attract litter. No Littering was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Do Not Litter Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6b1.title: Non-Potable Water
1f6b1.description: A water tap with a red stroke through it, indicating that water is not safe for drinking (non-potable). May be used at a camp site or other area that has water suitable for cleaning or other non-drinking purposes. Non-Potable Water was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Non-Potable Water Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6b7.title: No Pedestrians
1f6b7.description: A pedestrian symbol with a red stroke through it, indicating that pedestrians are prohibited from this location. May be seen in dedicated bike lanes, highways, or other areas not suitable to be on-foot. No Pedestrians was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4f5.title: No Mobile Phones
1f4f5.description: A mobile phone with a red stroke through it, indicating that mobile phones should not be present. Often seen in restricted areas, such as Customs or Passport Control. No Mobile Phones was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f51e.title: No One Under Eighteen
1f51e.description: The number eighteen with a red stroke through it, indicating a location where a person must be aged 18 or above to enter. The Samsung version of this emoji displays the number 19 instead of 18. This may be due to the practice of counting the first year of life as one (not zero) in parts of East Asia such as South Korea (the location of the Samsung Headquarters). No One Under Eighteen was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “No One Under Eighteen Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2622-fe0f.title: Radioactive
2622-fe0f.description: A hazard symbol for radiation or radioactivity. May appear similar to a three-pronged fan at small sizes. Generally displayed on an orange or yellow background. Radioactive was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Radioactive Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2623-fe0f.title: Biohazard
2623-fe0f.description: Biohazard was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Biohazard Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2b06-fe0f.title: Up Arrow
2b06-fe0f.description: An arrow, pointing up. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Up Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 under the name “Upwards Black Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2197-fe0f.title: Up-Right Arrow
2197-fe0f.description: An arrow pointing diagonally in an up-right, or north-east direction. Up-Right Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “North East Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

27a1-fe0f.title: Right Arrow
27a1-fe0f.description: An arrow, pointing right. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Right Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Black Rightwards Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2198-fe0f.title: Down-Right Arrow
2198-fe0f.description: An arrow pointing diagonally in an down-right, or south-east direction. Down-Right Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “South East Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2b07-fe0f.title: Down Arrow
2b07-fe0f.description: An arrow, pointing down. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Down Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 under the name “Downwards Black Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2199-fe0f.title: Down-Left Arrow
2199-fe0f.description: An arrow pointing diagonally in an down-left, or south-west direction. Down-Left Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “South West Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2b05-fe0f.title: Left Arrow
2b05-fe0f.description: An arrow, pointing left. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Left Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 under the name “Leftwards Black Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2196-fe0f.title: Up-Left Arrow
2196-fe0f.description: An arrow pointing diagonally in an up-left, or north-west direction. Up-Left Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “North West Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2195-fe0f.title: Up-Down Arrow
2195-fe0f.description: A vertical line with arrowheads on both ends, pointing up and down. Up-Down Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Up Down Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2194-fe0f.title: Left-Right Arrow
2194-fe0f.description: A horizontal line with arrowheads on both ends, pointing left and right. Left-Right Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Left Right Arrow” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

21a9-fe0f.title: Right Arrow Curving Left
21a9-fe0f.description: An arrow pointing to the left, with a curved hook at the other end. Similar in appearance to a sideways U Turn symbol, or a reply icon in an email application. Right Arrow Curving Left was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Leftwards Arrow With Hook” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

21aa-fe0f.title: Left Arrow Curving Right
21aa-fe0f.description: An arrow pointing to the right, with a curved hook at the other end. Similar in appearance to a sideways U Turn symbol, or a forward icon in an email application. Left Arrow Curving Right was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Rightwards Arrow With Hook” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2934-fe0f.title: Right Arrow Curving Up
aliases: Arrow Pointing Rightwards Then Curving Upwards
2934-fe0f.description: A curved arrow pointing up. Right Arrow Curving Up was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 under the name “Arrow Pointing Rightwards Then Curving Upwards” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2935-fe0f.title: Right Arrow Curving Down
aliases: Arrow Pointing Rightwards Then Curving Downwards
2935-fe0f.description: A curved arrow pointing down. Right Arrow Curving Down was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 under the name “Arrow Pointing Rightwards Then Curving Downwards” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f503.title: Clockwise Vertical Arrows
aliases: Clockwise Downwards and Upwards Open Circle Arrows
1f503.description: Clockwise Vertical Arrows was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clockwise Downwards and Upwards Open Circle Arrows” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f504.title: Counterclockwise Arrows Button
aliases: Anticlockwise Downwards and Upwards Open Circle Arrows
1f504.description: Two arrows forming a circle, pointing in an anticlockwise direction. Similar to symbols sometimes used for refresh or rotate. May also be used to indicate a task is in progress. Previously showed in a clockwise direction on Windows. Counterclockwise Arrows Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Anticlockwise Downwards and Upwards Open Circle Arrows” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f519.title: Back Arrow
1f519.description: Back Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Back With Leftwards Arrow Above” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f51a.title: End Arrow
1f51a.description: End Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “End With Leftwards Arrow Above” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f51b.title: On! Arrow
aliases: On With Exclamation Mark With Left Right Arrow Above
1f51b.description: On! Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “On With Exclamation Mark With Left Right Arrow Above” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f51c.title: Soon Arrow
1f51c.description: The word "soon" with an arrow above it, pointing to the right. Soon Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Soon With Rightwards Arrow Above” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f51d.title: Top Arrow
1f51d.description: The word "top" with an arrow pointing up above it. Top Arrow was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Top With Upwards Arrow Above” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6d0.title: Place of Worship
1f6d0.description: A building used for worship by people of any faith or religion. Examples include a church, mosque, or synagogue. A person is shown on their knees praying, in this symbol. Multi-faith places of worship are commonly found at airports. Place of Worship was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

269b-fe0f.title: Atom Symbol
269b-fe0f.description: Atom Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f549-fe0f.title: Om
1f549-fe0f.description: A symbol often used in relation to the religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism. Om was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Om Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2721-fe0f.title: Star of David
2721-fe0f.description: A symbol often used in relation to the religion of Judaism. Not to be confused with the Six Pointed Star With Middle Dot emoji. Star of David was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2638-fe0f.title: Wheel of Dharma
2638-fe0f.description: A symbol often used in relation to the Indian religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism and Jainism. Wheel of Dharma was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

262f-fe0f.title: Yin Yang
262f-fe0f.description: Yin Yang was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

271d-fe0f.title: Latin Cross
271d-fe0f.description: A latin cross, otherwise known as a Christian cross. This cross symbol is often used as a symbol of Christianity. Similar in appearance to the Orthodox cross. Latin Cross was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2626-fe0f.title: Orthodox Cross
2626-fe0f.description: Orthodox Cross was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

262a-fe0f.title: Star and Crescent
262a-fe0f.description: The crescent moon and star is a symbol often associated with the religion of Islam. This symbol can be found on the flags of many countries, such as Algeria, Azerbaijan, Malaysia, Pakistan and Turkey. Star and Crescent was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

262e-fe0f.title: Peace Symbol
262e-fe0f.description: A circular symbol, commonly used as a representation of peace. Alternatives include the Victory Hand, or the Dove of Peace. Peace Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f54e.title: Menorah
1f54e.description: A menorah showing nine lit candles, used on the Jewish holiday of Hanukkah. Menorah was approved as part of Unicode 8.0 in 2015 under the name “Menorah With Nine Branches” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f52f.title: Dotted Six-Pointed Star
aliases: Six Pointed Star With Middle Dot
1f52f.description: A star with six points, and a dot in the center. Similar to the Star of David emoji. Dotted Six-Pointed Star was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Six Pointed Star With Middle Dot” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

264a.title: Gemini
264a.description: The Gemini astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents Twins. Gemini was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

264b.title: Cancer
264b.description: The Cancer astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Crab. Cancer was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

264c.title: Leo
264c.description: The Leo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Lion. Leo was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

264d.title: Virgo
264d.description: The Virgo astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Maiden. Virgo was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

264e.title: Libra
264e.description: The Libra astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents weighing scales. Libra was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

264f.title: Scorpio
264f.description: The Scorpius astrological sign in the Zodiac. This Zodiac Symbol represents a Scorpion. Scorpio was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Scorpius” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26ce.title: Ophiuchus
26ce.description: Ophiuchus is used by some as a 13th sign in the Zodiac. The symbol for ophiuchus appears a U shape with a wavy line through it. Ophiuchus was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f500.title: Shuffle Tracks Button
1f500.description: Two arrows pointing right while crossing over one another. Used to indicate putting music on shuffle: randomizing the order of tracks in the upcoming playlist. May also be used to indicate two items switching places. Shuffle Tracks Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Twisted Rightwards Arrows” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f501.title: Repeat Button
aliases: Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows
1f501.description: Circular arrows pointing in a clockwise direction. Used in music player applications to loop a track or album continuously. Commonly used to repesent a retweet on Twitter. Repeat Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f502.title: Repeat Single Button
aliases: Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows With Circled One Overlay
1f502.description: Arrows pointing in a clockwise direction, with a number 1 badge in the lower corner.  Used in music player applications to loop a track or album once. Repeat Single Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Clockwise Rightwards and Leftwards Open Circle Arrows With Circled One Overlay” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

25b6-fe0f.title: Play Button
25b6-fe0f.description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing right. Commonly used as a symbol for play. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Play Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Black Right-Pointing Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23e9.title: Fast-Forward Button
23e9.description: Two triangles pointing to the right. Most commonly used as a symbol for fast forwarding media such as video tapes, CDs, or digital audio and video. Fast-Forward Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Right-Pointing Double Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23ed-fe0f.title: Next Track Button
aliases: Black Right-Pointing Double Triangle With Vertical Bar
23ed-fe0f.description: A symbol used in media players to indicate skipping to the next track (or scene). Shown as two triangles pointing right followed by a vertical bar. Next Track Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Right-Pointing Double Triangle With Vertical Bar” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23ef-fe0f.title: Play or Pause Button
aliases: Black Right-Pointing Triangle With Double Vertical Bar
23ef-fe0f.description: A play-pause icon, showing a right-pointing triangle (play) next to a double vertical bar (pause). Play or Pause Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Right-Pointing Triangle With Double Vertical Bar” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

25c0-fe0f.title: Reverse Button
25c0-fe0f.description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing left. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Reverse Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Black Left-Pointing Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23ea.title: Fast Reverse Button
23ea.description: Two triangles pointing to the left. Most commonly used as a symbol for rewinding media such as video tapes, CDs, or digital audio and video. Fast Reverse Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Left-Pointing Double Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23ee-fe0f.title: Last Track Button
aliases: Black Left-Pointing Double Triangle With Vertical Bar
23ee-fe0f.description: A symbol used in media players to indicate skipping to the first or previous track (or scene). Shown as a vertical bar followed by two triangles pointing left. Last Track Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Left-Pointing Double Triangle With Vertical Bar” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f53c.title: Upwards Button
1f53c.description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing up. Styled similarly to the left and right pointing triangles on iOS, but shown in red on Windows, and orange on Android. Upwards Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Up-Pointing Small Red Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23eb.title: Fast Up Button
23eb.description: Two triangles pointing up. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° clockwise. Fast Up Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Up-Pointing Double Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f53d.title: Downwards Button
1f53d.description: A triangle-shaped arrow, pointing down. Styled similarly to the left and right pointing triangles on iOS, but shown in red on Windows, and orange on Android. Downwards Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Down-Pointing Small Red Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23ec.title: Fast Down Button
23ec.description: Two triangles pointing down. Similar to rewind icon, rotated 90° counter-clockwise. Fast Down Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Black Down-Pointing Double Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23f8-fe0f.title: Pause Button
23f8-fe0f.description: A pause icon, displayed as two vertical bars. Pause Button was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Double Vertical Bar” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23f9-fe0f.title: Stop Button
23f9-fe0f.description: A stop icon, displayed as a square. Stop Button was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Black Square for Stop” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23fa-fe0f.title: Record Button
23fa-fe0f.description: A record icon, displayed as a circle. Record Button was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Black Circle for Record” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

23cf-fe0f.title: Eject Button
23cf-fe0f.description: An eject symbol, displayed as an upward-pointing triangle above a horiztonal bar. May be used as a physical button or an icon in a user interface. Represents the action of ejecting physical media such as a floppy disk, videocasette or DVD on a computer or media player. Eject Button was approved as part of Unicode 4.0 in 2003 under the name “Eject Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3a6.title: Cinema
1f3a6.description: An emoji representing the cinema: a large screen showing the latest movies, available to the public. Displayed by most platforms as a film projector symbol, and previously by Google and Microsoft as a cinema screen with curtains. Cinema was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f505.title: Dim Button
1f505.description: An icon of a outlined sun, used when decreasing the brightness of a screen. Appears smaller than the High Brightness Symbol. Dim Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Low Brightness Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f506.title: Bright Button
1f506.description: An icon of a outlined sun, used when increasing the brightness of a screen. Appears larger than the Low Brightness Symbol. Bright Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “High Brightness Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4f6.title: Antenna Bars
1f4f6.description: Bars increasing in height, showing the strength of the mobile (cellular) phone signal. More bars signifies better reception. Antenna Bars was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Antenna With Bars” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4f3.title: Vibration Mode
1f4f3.description: An icon representing vibration mode on a mobile phone, indicating that a phone should be switched to silent and/or vibrate mode. Displayed as a phone with either zig-zag lines or muted-bell icon on most platforms. Early versions of this emoji often used a heart alongside a mobile phone, as commonly seen in Japan. Vibration Mode was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4f4.title: Mobile Phone Off
1f4f4.description: A sign indicating that mobile phones should be turned off. Used in situations such as a cinema or live performance. Displayed as a mobile phone with the word OFF. Shown with a cross instead of the word OFF on Windows. Mobile Phone Off was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

267b-fe0f.title: Recycling Symbol
267b-fe0f.description: The universal recycling symbol, featuring three arrows pointing clockwise in a triangular formation. The word “black” in the official name is due to this emoji existing as a unicode character before the current standardized emoji set. Recycling Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 under the name “Black Universal Recycling Symbol” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

269c-fe0f.title: Fleur-de-lis
269c-fe0f.description: A decorative symbol that appears like a golden flower, but found in all manner of logos, symbols, and patterns. This symbol forms part of the World Scout Emblem, amongst other uses. Fleur-de-lis was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f531.title: Trident Emblem
1f531.description: A trident is a three-pronged spear, that appears similar to a pitchfork. Often held by Greek or Roman Gods in statues. Trident Emblem was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4db.title: Name Badge
1f4db.description: A name badge, used to identify oneself in a location that others may not know your name, such as a school trip, or a work conference. This tulip-shaped name badge is one of many designs commonly found at kindergartens in Japan. Name Badge was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f530.title: Japanese Symbol for Beginner
1f530.description: A yellow and green shield symbol, called a Shoshinsha Mark. Must be displayed by drivers in Japan for one year after they receive their drivers licence. Similar to L-Plates used to identify learner drivers in other countries. Japanese Symbol for Beginner was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2b55.title: Hollow Red Circle
