2b55.description: Used as an alternative to a check (tick) in Japan for a something that is correct. The opposite of an X (cross mark) for something wrong. Hollow Red Circle was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 under the name “Heavy Large Circle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2611-fe0f.title: Check Box With Check
2611-fe0f.description: A checkbox showing a check mark inside the box. Not to be confused with the similarly named Ballot Box With Ballot emoji. This emoji is not supported in Twitter names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Check Box With Check was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Ballot Box With Check” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2714-fe0f.title: Check Mark
2714-fe0f.description: A thick (heavy) check mark displayed on some platforms in a handwritten style. Generally displayed in black on most platforms, except Android (blue), Windows (green) and Samsung (red). This emoji is not supported in Twitter names, possibly in an attempt to minimize confusion with a verified checkmark. Check Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Heavy Check Mark” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2716-fe0f.title: Multiplication Sign
2716-fe0f.description: Multiplication Sign was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Heavy Multiplication X” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

274c.title: Cross Mark
274c.description: A large red cross mark, displayed in the shape of a letter X and similar to a multiplication sign. Cross Mark was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

274e.title: Cross Mark Button
274e.description: Cross Mark Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Negative Squared Cross Mark” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

27b0.title: Curly Loop
27b0.description: A curled loop, which is shown in black on most platforms. Displayed as a blue ribbon on Samsung devices. Similar to the Double Curly Loop but with only a single loop. Curly Loop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

27bf.title: Double Curly Loop
27bf.description: Two curly loops, which represent a reel-to-reel tape recorder. Used as a symbol for voicemail on many phones. A variation of this logo is used by Free Dial, a toll-free telephone number by NTT in Japan. Double Curly Loop was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

303d-fe0f.title: Part Alternation Mark
303d-fe0f.description: Used in traditional Japanese music such as Noh or Renga, to indicate the start of a song. More specifically, the part alternation mark is displayed where the singer’s part begins. This symbol looks sort of like a lopsided capital M; or a rollercoaster track showing a dip, and then a drop off to the right. Part Alternation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2733-fe0f.title: Eight-Spoked Asterisk
2733-fe0f.description: Used in a similar manner to a regular * asterisk character but tends to be shown in a similar vertical alignment to a • bullet point. The eight spoked asterisk has both a ✳︎ text and ✳️ emoji presentation available on most platforms. Eight-Spoked Asterisk was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Eight Spoked Asterisk” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2734-fe0f.title: Eight-Pointed Star
2734-fe0f.description: A star with eight points, that is commonly shown in orange, and for some reason, with only four points. See the glossary for information on the term black in unicode character names. Eight-Pointed Star was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Eight Pointed Black Star” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2747-fe0f.title: Sparkle
2747-fe0f.description: Used a decorative bullet-point, the sparkle has both a ❇︎ text and ❇️ emoji presentation available on most platforms. Sparkle was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

203c-fe0f.title: Double Exclamation Mark
203c-fe0f.description: Double Exclamation Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2049-fe0f.title: Exclamation Question Mark
aliases: Red Exclamation Mark and Question Mark
2049-fe0f.description: Exclamation Question Mark was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

3030-fe0f.title: Wavy Dash
3030-fe0f.description: Just like a regular dash (hyphen), sometimes used in Asian character sets in the same way a – or — is used in latin character sets. Wavy Dash was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

00a9-fe0f.title: Copyright
00a9-fe0f.description: Copyright was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Copyright Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

00ae-fe0f.title: Registered
00ae-fe0f.description: Registered was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Registered Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2122-fe0f.title: Trade Mark
2122-fe0f.description: A trademark symbol, the letters TM displayed after a word that is trademarked. Trade Mark was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Trade Mark Sign” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f51f.title: Keycap: 10
1f51f.description: The number 10 on a square with rounded corners, designed to look like a keycap. Keycap: 10 was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Keycap Ten” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f520.title: Input Latin Uppercase
aliases: Input Symbol for Latin Capital Letters
1f520.description: A symbol showing the capital letters A, B, C and D. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle capital letter input. Input Latin Uppercase was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Input Symbol for Latin Capital Letters” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f521.title: Input Latin Lowercase
aliases: Input Symbol for Latin Small Letters
1f521.description: A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to toggle lowercase letter input. Input Latin Lowercase was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Input Symbol for Latin Small Letters” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f522.title: Input Numbers
1f522.description: A symbol showing the numbers 1, 2, 3 and 4. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable symbol input, as opposed to alphabetical or symbol input. Input Numbers was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Input Symbol for Numbers” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f523.title: Input Symbols
1f523.description: A symbol showing the following glyphs: 〒 (Japanese postal mark), 𝅘𝅥𝅮 (music note), & (ampersand, or sometimes an @ symbol) and % (percentage sign). Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable symbol input, as opposed to alphabetical or numeric input. Input Symbols was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Input Symbol for Symbols” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f524.title: Input Latin Letters
1f524.description: A symbol showing the lowercase letters a, b, c and d. Intended to be used on a software keyboard, or other input screen to enable alphabetical input, as opposed to numeric or symbol input. Input Latin Letters was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Input Symbol for Latin Letters” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f170-fe0f.title: A Button (Blood Type)
aliases: Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter A
1f170-fe0f.description: A symbol representing Blood Type A. Displayed as the letter A on a red background. A Button (Blood Type) was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter A” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f18e.title: AB Button (Blood Type)
1f18e.description: A symbol representing Blood Type AB. Displayed as the letters AB on a red background. AB Button (Blood Type) was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Negative Squared AB” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f171-fe0f.title: B Button (Blood Type)
aliases: Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter B
1f171-fe0f.description: A symbol representing Blood Type B. Displayed as the letter B on a red background. Sometimes used online to replace the letter C at the start of words in reference to the Bloods street gang's practice of turning words like cool into bool. This has expanded in some instances to starting any word with the letter B, or more specifically, this emoji which makes it more 🅱️lear that a letter has been replaced. B Button (Blood Type) was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter B” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f191.title: CL Button
1f191.description: CL is what shows on the CLear button of some older mobile phones. CL Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CL” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f192.title: Cool Button
1f192.description: The word cool, shown enclosed in a square. This generally displays in a shade of blue, or blue-gray on most platforms. Used as a text decoration. Cool Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared Cool” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f193.title: Free Button
1f193.description: The word free, shown enclosed in a square. Free Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared Free” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2139-fe0f.title: Information
2139-fe0f.description: A lowercase letter i, enclosed in a rounded square or circle. Implemented in apps or websites to indicate that help or further information is available. May be used as a logo for tourist information signage in a town or city. Information was approved as part of Unicode 3.0 in 1999 under the name “Information Source” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f194.title: ID Button
1f194.description: The letters ID in a square. ID Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared ID” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

24c2-fe0f.title: Circled M
24c2-fe0f.description: The letter M in a circle, commonly used in to identify a Metro (subway, underground train) station in a city area. Circled M was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Circled Latin Capital Letter M” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f195.title: New Button
1f195.description: The word new, shown enclosed in a square. New Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared New” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f196.title: NG Button
1f196.description: The letters NG, shown enclosed in a square, which are an acronym for the words No Good. The origin of NG refers to bloopers shown during or after the credits of a live television show in Japan (known as NGs), but can be used in any field as a form of shorthand for no good. NG Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared NG” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f17e-fe0f.title: O Button (Blood Type)
aliases: Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter O
1f17e-fe0f.description: A symbol representing Blood Type O. Displayed as the letter O on a red background. O Button (Blood Type) was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter O” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f197.title: OK Button
1f197.description: The letters OK, shown enclosed in a square. Meaning Okay, denoting approval. The opposite of the Squared NG Emoji. OK Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared OK” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f17f-fe0f.title: P Button
aliases: Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter P
1f17f-fe0f.description: P Button was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 under the name “Negative Squared Latin Capital Letter P” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f198.title: SOS Button
1f198.description: SOS is the description for the distress signal in Morse Code. This emoji means SOS or “emergency”. SOS Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared SOS” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f199.title: Up! Button
1f199.description: The word up with an exclamation point after it, shown enclosed in a square. Originally intended to denote leveling up in a game. Up! Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared Up With Exclamation Mark” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f19a.title: Vs Button
1f19a.description: Vs Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared Vs” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f201.title: Japanese “Here” Button
1f201.description: Means “Here” in Japanese, referring to a destination. Japanese “Here” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared Katakana Koko” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f202-fe0f.title: Japanese “Service Charge” Button
1f202-fe0f.description: Translates as meaning complimentary, or free of charge. For example, a drink that is given "on the house" to a regular customer. Japanese “Service Charge” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared Katakana Sa” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f237-fe0f.title: Japanese “Monthly Amount” Button
1f237-fe0f.description: CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Means “moon” or “month” in Chinese. Japanese “Monthly Amount” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6708” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f236.title: Japanese “Not Free of Charge” Button
aliases: Japanese Sign Meaning “Not Free of Charge”
1f236.description: This emoji means to own or posses. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Not Free of Charge” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6709” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f22f.title: Japanese “Reserved” Button
1f22f.description: This character translates as meaning a finger or toe pointing to indicate a certain direction. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Reserved” Button was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6307” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f250.title: Japanese “Bargain” Button
1f250.description: Denotes a “good bargain” in Japanese. Japanese “Bargain” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Circled Ideograph Advantage” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f239.title: Japanese “Discount” Button
1f239.description: Symbol for a sale, or bargain prices in Japan (“cut prices”). Literally translated, this character means to cut or divide. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Discount” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-5272” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f21a.title: Japanese “Free of Charge” Button
1f21a.description: This means to lack, or have none of something. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Free of Charge” Button was approved as part of Unicode 5.2 in 2009 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7121” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f232.title: Japanese “Prohibited” Button
1f232.description: This Emoji means “prohibit, restrict or forbid” in Japanese. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Prohibited” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7981” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f251.title: Japanese “Acceptable” Button
1f251.description: Japanese “Acceptable” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Circled Ideograph Accept” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f238.title: Japanese “Application” Button
1f238.description: This Emoji has two meanings. One meaning is “request” in Japanese. An alternative meaning is “monkey” in the Chinese zodiac. It is commonly used in Japan to denote an application form or contact information for inquiries. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Application” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7533” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f234.title: Japanese “Passing Grade” Button
1f234.description: Means “agreement” in Japanese. More literally, it means to unite, or join together. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Passing Grade” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-5408” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f233.title: Japanese “Vacancy” Button
1f233.description: This 空 character means empty and available in Japanese. This is used in the context of an empty parking space or a vacant hotel room. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Vacancy” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-7a7a” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

3297-fe0f.title: Japanese “Congratulations” Button
3297-fe0f.description: Translated from Japanese, this means "congratulations" or "pray for happiness". Japanese “Congratulations” Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Circled Ideograph Congratulation” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

3299-fe0f.title: Japanese “Secret” Button
3299-fe0f.description: Japanese “Secret” Button was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 under the name “Circled Ideograph Secret” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f23a.title: Japanese “Open for Business” Button
1f23a.description: Means “work” in Japanese.  This Emoji used to mean “open for business” and precedes business hours. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “Open for Business” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-55b6” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f235.title: Japanese “No Vacancy” Button
1f235.description: This emoji means “full” in Japanese, usually used to denote “full capacity” such as a gas/petrol tank on a car or pre-paid phone card. CJK Ideographs are characters used in Chinese, Japanese and Korean languages. Their writing systems all completely or partly use Chinese characters. Japanese “No Vacancy” Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Squared CJK Unified Ideograph-6e80” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f534.title: Red Circle
1f534.description: Red Circle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Large Red Circle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f535.title: Blue Circle
1f535.description: Blue Circle was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Large Blue Circle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26ab.title: Black Circle
26ab.description: Black Circle was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 under the name “Medium Black Circle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

26aa.title: White Circle
26aa.description: White Circle was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 under the name “Medium White Circle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2b1b.title: Black Large Square
2b1b.description: Black Large Square was approved as part of Unicode 5.1 in 2008 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

2b1c.title: White Large Square
2b1c.description: White Large Square was approved as part of Unicode 5.1 in 2008 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

25fc-fe0f.title: Black Medium Square
25fc-fe0f.description: Black Medium Square was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

25fb-fe0f.title: White Medium Square
25fb-fe0f.description: White Medium Square was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

25fe.title: Black Medium-Small Square
25fe.description: Black Medium-Small Square was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 under the name “Black Medium Small Square” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

25fd.title: White Medium-Small Square
25fd.description: White Medium-Small Square was approved as part of Unicode 3.2 in 2002 under the name “White Medium Small Square” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

25aa-fe0f.title: Black Small Square
25aa-fe0f.description: Black Small Square was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

25ab-fe0f.title: White Small Square
25ab-fe0f.description: White Small Square was approved as part of Unicode 1.1 in 1993 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f536.title: Large Orange Diamond
1f536.description: A larger version of the small orange diamond emoji. Large Orange Diamond was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f537.title: Large Blue Diamond
1f537.description: Large Blue Diamond was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f538.title: Small Orange Diamond
1f538.description: A small version of the large orange diamond emoji. Small Orange Diamond was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f539.title: Small Blue Diamond
1f539.description: Small Blue Diamond was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f53a.title: Red Triangle Pointed Up
1f53a.description: Red Triangle Pointed Up was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Up-Pointing Red Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f53b.title: Red Triangle Pointed Down
1f53b.description: Red Triangle Pointed Down was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Down-Pointing Red Triangle” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f4a0.title: Diamond With a Dot
aliases: Diamond Shape With a Dot Inside
1f4a0.description: A glyph that is used for kawaii in Japan, resembling the shape of a flower. Diamond With a Dot was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Diamond Shape With a Dot Inside” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f518.title: Radio Button
1f518.description: A radio button user interface element, used in form fields with two or more choices. Differs from a checkbox, in that only one response can be selected. This emoji generally shows the on/enabled state for the radio button, with a smaller circle inside a larger outer circle. Radio Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f533.title: White Square Button
1f533.description: White Square Button. White Square Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f532.title: Black Square Button
1f532.description: Black Square Button was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3c1.title: Chequered Flag
1f3c1.description: A flag with black and white squares shown in a checkerboard pattern, used to signal the start or end of a motor car race. Chequered Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f6a9.title: Triangular Flag
1f6a9.description: A triangular red flag on a post. Most commonly associated with golf, as shown in the flag in hole emoji. Triangular Flag was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 under the name “Triangular Flag on Post” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f38c.title: Crossed Flags
1f38c.description: Two Japanese Flags, crossed at the base. Except on some Samsung devices, which have previously displayed two South Korean flags. Crossed Flags was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3f4.title: Black Flag
1f3f4.description: Black Flag was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Waving Black Flag” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f3f3-fe0f.title: White Flag
1f3f3-fe0f.description: A white flag, shown waving on a post. Traditionally used as a sign of surrender, the meaning of this flag as an emoji is less defined. White Flag was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name “Waving White Flag” and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1e8.title: Flag: Ascension Island
1f1e6-1f1e8.description: The flag for Ascension Island, which may show as the letters AC on some platforms. This same flag is used for St. Helena and Tristan Da Cunha. The Flag: Ascension Island emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇨 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter C emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Ascension Island was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1e9.title: Flag: Andorra
1f1e6-1f1e9.description: The flag for Andorra, which may show as the letters AD on some platforms. The Flag: Andorra emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇩 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter D emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Andorra was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1ea.title: Flag: United Arab Emirates
1f1e6-1f1ea.description: The flag for United Arab Emirates, which may show as the letters AE on some platforms. The Flag: United Arab Emirates emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇪 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter E emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: United Arab Emirates was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1eb.title: Flag: Afghanistan
1f1e6-1f1eb.description: The flag for Afghanistan, which may show as the letters AF on some platforms. The Flag: Afghanistan emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇫 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter F emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Afghanistan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1ec.title: Flag: Antigua & Barbuda
1f1e6-1f1ec.description: The Flag: Antigua & Barbuda emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇬 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter G emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Antigua & Barbuda was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1ee.title: Flag: Anguilla
1f1e6-1f1ee.description: The flag for Anguilla, which may show as the letters AI on some platforms. The Flag: Anguilla emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇮 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter I emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Anguilla was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1f1.title: Flag: Albania
1f1e6-1f1f1.description: The flag for Albania, which may show as the letters AL on some platforms. The Flag: Albania emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇱 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter L emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Albania was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1f2.title: Flag: Armenia
1f1e6-1f1f2.description: The flag for Armenia, which may show as the letters AM on some platforms. The Flag: Armenia emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇲 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter M emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Armenia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1f4.title: Flag: Angola
1f1e6-1f1f4.description: The flag for Angola, which may show as the letters A and O on some platforms. The Flag: Angola emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇴 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter O emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Angola was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1f6.title: Flag: Antarctica
1f1e6-1f1f6.description: The flag for Antarctica, which may show as the letters AQ on some platforms. The Flag: Antarctica emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇶 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter Q emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Antarctica was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1f7.title: Flag: Argentina
1f1e6-1f1f7.description: The flag for Argentina, which may show as the letters AR on some platforms. The Flag: Argentina emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇷 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter R emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Argentina was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1f8.title: Flag: American Samoa
1f1e6-1f1f8.description: The flag for American Samoa, which may show as the letters AS on some platforms. The Flag: American Samoa emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇸 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter S emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: American Samoa was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1f9.title: Flag: Austria
1f1e6-1f1f9.description: The flag for Austria, which may show as the letters AT on some platforms. The Flag: Austria emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Austria was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1e6-1f1fa.title: Flag: Australia
1f1e6-1f1fa.description: The flag for Australia, which may show as the letters AU on some platforms. The Flag: Australia emoji is a sequence of the 🇦 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter A and 🇺 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter U emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Australia was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.

1f1f9-1f1fc.description: The flag for Taiwan (officially Republic of China), which may show as the letters TW on some platforms. This Taiwanese flag is hidden from the emoji keyboard on iOS devices when the region is set to China mainland or (as of iOS 13.1.2) Hong Kong or Macau. Chinese-model iPhones will not display this emoji and will instead show a missing character tofu (☒) in place of the flag, as will iOS devices with region set to China mainland. Hong Kong and Macua only hide this emoji from the emoji keyboard. The Flag: Taiwan emoji is a sequence of the 🇹 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter T and 🇼 Regional Indicator Symbol Letter W emojis. These display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Flag: Taiwan was added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.
